The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Phase 2 Scope of Work for Base Period
 
 The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.
 
 
 
 Phase 2:
 
 1. The attached work plan represents the aims and work to be carried out by the subcontractor to achieve the project goals.
 2. Subcontractor is required to provide a monthly invoice that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifth of the following month.  First report is due May 5, 2012.  Additional information should be included in the monthly report.  The monthly report format may change if CMS requests additional or different information on the monthly report.  An example monthly report template is attached.
 3. Consistent flow of data in from the Subcontractor s hospitals of at least 80%.
 4. Participation by Subcontractor program personnel at Contractor s national learning activities.
 5. An annual report at the end of 2012 and 2013.

column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTECHNOLOGY)
column76:
The proposed two-year project will build upon the considerable base of our ongoing NICHD contract work that has established the use of intracortical recordings in humans for long periods (>1 year) and begun to demonstrate the feasibility of using such recordings in a brain-computer interface used by a completely paralyzed person to control the FES-reanimated movements of the arm. The proposed project will continue the study of one existing participant, will add two new contract-supported participants, and will likely include information obtained from at least one additional participant from a separate study. This significant increase in the number of participants will allow us to begin to reach more general conclusions about the feasibility of intracortical recordings as the basis of an effective FES user interface. The timing of our proposed two-year project is also fortuitous, for at least two reasons: (1) A new family of neuroprosthesis devices connected together by a networked design will begin human trials in a separate study within the next year, and this will also serve as the basis of an advanced neuroprosthesis for restoring arm movements to individuals with high tetraplegia (the group targeted by the proposed study) within the next several years. A high-performance intracortical interface could be easily interfaced with this advanced neuroprosthesis to complete a breakthrough rehabilitation treatment for these individuals. (2) The development of a fully implanted neural recording system is also approaching human deployment, which would alleviate concerns with combining an implanted FES system with a percutaneous BCI system, while also completing the long-standing goal of deploying a completely implanted, BCI-controlled FES system for restoring arm movements. The results of the proposed two-year project will thus provide critical information on the command and control algorithms needed to complete a fully implanted, BCI-controlled FES system that reanimates the arm and hand of individuals with complete paralysis.
  Over the next two years, we will further develop signal processing and decoder techniques that use multiple signal modalities to increase the robustness of control and can take into account the non-stationarities associated with cortical control. We will complete the development of a real-time, 11 DOF Dynamic Arm Simulator, and continue to develop computer-based visualizations that are immersive and compelling enough to the participants to allow relevant evaluations of both BCI and proposed FES controller algorithms before actually implanting a real FES system. We will explore several fundamental properties of our intracortical interface using these methods, including (1) determining how many arm DOF can be simultaneously controlled in a continuous manner and which coordinate frame (joint vs. Cartesian) is optimal for intracortical control, (2) evaluating the use of goal-based decoding as a way to reduce the cognitive burden on the participant, (3) examining the feasibility of controlling functional hand grasp and wrist movements to perform standard activities of daily living hand via the same BrainGate2 systems used for control of the rest of the upper extremity, and (4) testing the ability of these same intracortical recordings to effectively control tasks where the user must produce forces rather than movements, and/or interact with objects that have their own mechanical dynamics. At the conclusion of this study, we will have acquired significant information that will guide the direction of the field (and our own research activities) for several years to come.

column67: Contracts and Grants,Educational Institution,Nonprofit Organization,Private University or College
column76: Approximately half of all new HIV infections in the U.S. stem from sexual risk behaviors of HIV-positive persons who are aware of their seropositive status. Approximately two-thirds of these HIV aware persons enter medical care within a year of being diagnosed. The HIV medical care setting is thus an ideal location for delivering a sustainable behavioral intervention to large numbers of HIV-positive persons, with the goal of improving patients' health and reducing the potential for transmission of HIV infection. To reach this goal, a comprehensive intervention is needed that not only addresses sexual and drug risk behaviors directly, but also attempts to improve patients' retention in medical care and their adherence to treatment regimens.

column43: TAS::75 0872::TAS  TRANSLATIONAL NANOMEDICALTHERAPIES FOR CARDIAC & VASCULAR DISEASES
column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
Work at BWH will mainly involve design, development and testing of nanoparticles which can release
 LXR agonist, GW3965 or IL-10. First PLGA-PEG-F polymers will be synthesized by the already developed techniques at BWH. These polymers will be used to construct nanoparticles via
 nanoprecipitation or double emulsion strategies. Encapsulation of LXR agonist in PLGA-PEG nanoparticles will be achieved via nanoprecipitation, while the IL-10 encapsulation is achieved by via double emulsion (water-in-oil-in-water) strategy; both the techniques were pioneered by the BWH group. First a series of nanoparticles with LXR agonist encapsulated in the PLGA core will be made via
 nanoprecipitation and studied for size, loading and encapsulation efficiencies. The best candidates will be short listed based on small size, higher loading and encapsulation efficiencies. Loading and EE will be measured by using HPLC. Further in vitro release profiles of agonist from these nanoparticles will be studied to decide the best compositions. A second series of nanoparticles with IL-10 encapsulated in the PLGA core will be made via double emulsion will be studied for size, loading and encapsulation efficiencies. Here BCA assay will be used to quantify the loading and EE of IL-10. Best nanoparticle with small size and high loading will be used for further in vitro release studies. Well characterized nanoparticles from the both will be used for in vitro studies to study the uptake and intracellular drug release. Further these nanoparticles will be shipped to co-PI labs at NY for further in vitro or in vivo studies. Also mouse model of atherosclerosis will be used to test the particle properties for plaque
 delivery, bioactivity of LXR agonist and IL-10 using LCM-RT-QPCR. Depending on the results the nanoparticle design and construction will be re visited. Further effect of LXR agonist and IL-10 released from the nanoparticles will be tested on the progession of atherosclerosis using mouse models by
 measuring end points like plaque size, cellular composition, fibrous cap thickness, inflammatory and antiinflammatory cytokines, UPR markers, apoptosis, plaque necrosis, in-situ efferocytosis and reverse cholesterol transport pathways. Further studies will be carried out to examine the plaque regression of atherosclerosis using mouse models.

column76: Dr. Sharpe's group is analyzing aged-related changes in CD8 T cell responses in  mice in close collaboration with Drs. Marcia Haigis and E. John Wherry. Dr Haigis group studies the role of sirtuins in the metabolic regulation of T cell responses in young and aged mice. The main goals of their studies are understand how sirtuins regulate (1) the role of key metabolic pathways in immune regulation, and  (2) to test the hypothesis that immune senescence can be attributed, at least partially, to metabolic malfunction.

MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations
 o Resource will support Regional Office VSI & RI Events
 
 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.
 
 Task 3: Lean Development Support
 MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in providing lean development support. The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource. 
   Specific activities associated with this support include, but are not limited to:
 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.
 2. Providing governance support to guide and monitor CMS continu

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

Attachment A
 Scope of Work for Harvard School of Public Health
 
 Background:  Harvard School of Public Health, will assist HRET in implementation of the AHRQ SUSP Ambulatory Surgery national project through providing expert input into overall strategy, assisting in monitoring key project metrics, providing necessary checklists, assisting in the development of the course design guide and improvement materials, and in training master trainers and change agents to support the project s implementation. HSOPH will also provide feedback to Westat regarding the SOPS for Ambulatory Surgery survey that will be developed. 
 
 Key Personnel:  The following individual/positions are designated as key personnel under this Agreement:
   Atul Guwande
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor plans to use and/or deliver the following pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights in its performance of this Agreement:
 
 - NONE
 
 Tasks:  
 
 1.  Participate in HRET-led efforts to identify and recruit TEP members and to plan and execute all TEP meetings required under the contract.
 2. Support the design, creation and enhancement of improvement resources required under the contract, including resources for participating facilities and for connector organizations working with these facilities.  Resources will include change packages (in electronic or print forms), Powerpoint presentations for use in meetings and on webinars, and video vignettes used to illustrate improvement concepts.  
 3. Provide feedback on the Ambulatory Surgery Center (ASC) Survey of Patient Safety Culture being developed by another HRET subcontractor and input on the ASC patient satisfaction measure being developed by CMS.
 4.  Supply checklists and other content relevant to the implementation guide and review and provide feedback on drafts of this document that HRET develops.  
 5. Support the implementation of ASC improvement activities by:
 a. Participating in the planning and execution of the stakeholder meeting.  
 b. Training the master trainers.  This will require helping HRET to conceptualize what training activities and materials are needed, serving as active participants in the planning and execution of these training activities, and providing ongoing coaching for trainees to fully equip them to work with ASCs.  
 c. Supporting the state-level implementation activities By attending kickoff meetings, leading webinars and conference calls with project participants, and mentoring other faculty performing these activities.
 6.  Assist in the selection of appropriate process and outcome measures for the project, provide feedback on resources that explain the measures and their validity to participants as well as how their data can be submitted, and assist HRET in reviewing the data and preparing reports for centers and the teams that are working with them.  
 7. Have at least one person on monthly planning calls with AHRQ and provide information HRET needs to complete monthly and other reports to AHRQ.

MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations
 o Resource will support Regional Office VSI & RI Events
 
 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.
 
 Task 3: Lean Development Support
 MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in providing lean development support. The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource. 
   Specific activities associated with this support include, but are not limited to:
 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.
 2. Providing governance support to guide and monitor CMS continu

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

column76: Conduct CDL and ADCC assays of human sera from the following experimental human viccine studies:  10 serasamples from H7N7 vaccine trial (pre- and postvaccination); 10 sera samples from H5N1 vaccine trial (pre- and post-vaccination); 5 sera samples from H7N7 LAIV/IV study (pre- and post vaccination); human mAbs to H7 (positive controls); and 3 sets of pre- and post-seasonal viccine sera and include seasonal H1 virus infected target cells in the CDL and ADCC assays.  These sera will be tested against target cells (A549) infected with wild type H7N9 strain, which is BSL3+ (alternatively could test attenuated H7N9 strains such as A/Shanghai/2/2103 generated for vaccine production, which is BSL2_).  As a positive control in the CDL and ADCC assays, target cells infected with either seasonal or 2009 pandemic H1N1 strain or a seasonal H3N2 strain will be used depending on when the serum samples were collected.

Program Management Support
 The Contractor shall provide support to best enable NIH oversight of the data Commons Consortium membership as they perform their responsibilities as defined through the Other Transactional Authority (OTA) negotiation process.  This includes the following activities:
 
 1. Within 15 business days of execution, the Contractor shall provide a strategy for establishing program management controls for the Data Commons, and the ongoing efforts consortium that underlies is. This will be vetted with key NIH stakeholders, modified as needed, and then finalized.  Key attributes of the strategy will include some or all of the following (to include mechanisms of achieving these goals):
 a. Risk enumeration
 b. Mitigation enumeration (based on a.)
 c. Integration of consortium activities
 d. Cross-team coordination 
 e. Dependency enumeration 
 f. Program governance 
 g. Data governance
 h. Standards assurance  
 i. Accountability management
 j. Financial tracking (cost, value)
 k. Infrastructure planning
 l. Enumeration of continuous improvement opportunities
 
 The required contents of the strategy document will be enumerated by MITRE within the first 5 business days of this contract, except by mutual agreement of MITRE, NIH, and Contractor.  It is expected that a 1-page document will suffice for these purposes.  
 
 2. Through this effort, including during finalization of the strategy for program management controls, the Contractor shall begin execution of portions that have been mutually agreed.  This means that supporting the overall management of this effort by ensuring the timely completion and coordination of objectives, refining NIH-derived metrics of success, and enhancing overall reporting and communication on the program can begin immediately.  Specific activities to be undertaken immediately include the following:
 a. Coordinate with Consortium project management personnel
 b. Monitor general project health
 c. Maintain master schedule of milestones and dependencies for all Data Commons activities based on the schedule provided initially by NIH
 d. Facilitate interdependent issues and risks mitigation
 e. Facilitate critical program meetings (no more than 12)
 f. Create executive-level presentations (no more than 6)
 g. Support and enforce adherence to project communications plan (mechanism TBD)
 h. Manage stakeholder engagement metrics (no more than monthly)
 i. Provide other support to Program Lead, as required and as appropriate for the position
 
 Contractor will provide reports on the activities undertaken and outcomes every 20 business days, in a format mutually agreeable to Contractor, NIH, and MITRE.  It is expected that a 1-3-page document will suffice for these purposes. 
 
 Task 3: Data Management Support
 The Contractor shall provide support to best enable NIH Data Management for the Data Commons Consortium membership as they perform their responsibilities as defined through the Other Transactional Authority (OTA) negotiation process. This includes the following activities:
 1. Within 15 business days of execution, the Contractor shall provide a strategy for establishing data management controls for the Data Commons, including (but not exclusive to) TOPMed and GTEx data and metadata, and the ongoing consortium efforts that underlies this. This will be vetted with key NIH stakeholders, modified as needed, and then finalized. Key attributes of the strategy will include some or all of the following (to include mechanisms of achieving these goals):
 a. Data migration (to cloud, inter-cloud, download from cloud)
 b. Data currency maintenance
 c. Metadata management
 d. Metadata configuration and management in SRA/SDDP/fusera or other NIH-prescribed access control mechanisms
 e. Data access control and user authentication
 f. Cloud data storage configuration and administration
 g. Data use measurement
 h. Data storage cost forecasts
 i. Data storage use forecasts
 j. Data governance
 k. Data availability communications

column76:
MITRE requires assistance in the delivery of federally funded research and development center
 ( FFRDC ) services to the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) for a project to
 establish and support the Health Care Payment Learning and Action Network ( LAN ). The objective
 of the LAN is to align CMS and private payers in moving payment from traditional Fee for Service
 ( FFS ) methods to FFS-linked to quality, alternative payment models, and population-based payment
 to achieve the stated goals of delivery system reform. By sharing information about successful models
 and encouraging private entities to share their best practices, the Center for Medicare & Medicaid
 Innovation ( CMMI ) intends to minimize barriers to adoption of alternative payment models.
 The LAN has defined progress in terms of rebalancing health care spending flowing through four
 categories of health care payments, which are:
   Category 1: FFS with no link to quality and value
   Category 2: FFS linked to quality and value
   Category 3: APMs built on FFS architecture
   Category 4: Population-based payment
 To help move the field toward Categories 3 and 4, the LAN independently convenes Action
 Collaboratives (ACs) comprised of stakeholders that have prioritized a commitment to adopting
 alternative payment models. The action collaboratives are focused on specific actionable goals   such as
 implementation of the LAN s maternity episode payment model recommendations in select regions
 across the U.S., and providing support for primary care payment transformation with an initial focus
 on the CMS Innovation Center s (CMMI) Comprehensive Primary Care Plus (CPC+) model. A future
 action collaborative will be focused on Accountable Care Organizations (ACOs.) This SOW is written
 to be generalizable to any Action Collaborative, regardless of subject matter.
 MITRE is the independent convener of LAN ACs, but operates in close partnership with CMMI and
 with guidance from the LAN Guiding Committee. The aim is to ensure that the virtual events
 orchestrated for AC participants create value for them, and move them closer to action by meeting
 their APM implementation goals and the agreed-upon, measurable goals.

 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.
 
 Task 3: Lean Development Support
 MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in providing lean development support. The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource. 
   Specific activities associated with this support include, but are not limited to:
 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

 in the Department of Health Care Policy at Harvard Medical School. Dr. Haiden Huskamp will
 serve as site PI, overseeing all phases of the work at Harvard, in addition to being involved in
 other aspects of the project. As detailed in the project's management plan, Ors. Huskamp and
 Stevenson, who have collaborated on research related to utilization of medications, long-term care
 services, and hospice and palliative care for over a decade, will be in regular contact throughout

 off of her prior work in using the required Medicare datasets.
 The primary analytic tasks that will occur at Harvard under the direction of Dr. Huskamp (along
 with Dr. Stevenson) center around the linkage of the primary data sources (Medicare claims, long
 term pharmacy claims, and Minimum Data Set (MOS) data) and analysis of the linked data. The
 analyses will utilize these datasets from 2010 through the most recent year of available data.

column76: The proposed work is divided into four tasks. Task 1 - Epitome Identification, The goal of Task 1 is to generate comprehensive, high-Resolution B cell epitome maps of RTA and RTB, with particular emphasis on discontinuous epitopes. Task 2-Epitope validation, The goal of Task 2 is to classify the B cell epitopes identified on RTA and RTB in Task 1 as being functional targets of toxin0neutralizing, non neutralizing or possibly even toxin-enhancing antibodies and to then determine, in the context of a polyclonal antibody response, their relative contributions to eliciting antibodies involved in protective immunity to ricin. Task 3- Data management and Epitope Submission, Submission of epitopes to IEDB. All immunological data generated unto this contract will be maintained at local collaborating institutions and sent to the Wadsworth Center for centralized storage. Submission of structure to PDB. Within six months of completion of ricin toxin B cell epitope verification and validation the Mantis laboratory will be responsible submitting detailed epitopes and related information to the IEDB. Task 4- Mechanisms of Antibody Protection, The goal of task 4 is to determine in detail the mechanisms by which murine mAbs and VHH identified and validated in Task 1 and 2 neutralize ricin, in vitro and in vivo.

column76:
The proposed two-year project will build upon the considerable base of our ongoing NICHD contract work that has established the use of intracortical recordings in humans for long periods (>1 year) and begun to demonstrate the feasibility of using such recordings in a brain-computer interface used by a completely paralyzed person to control the FES-reanimated movements of the arm. The proposed project will continue the study of one existing participant, will add two new contract-supported participants, and will likely include information obtained from at least one additional participant from a separate study. This significant increase in the number of participants will allow us to begin to reach more general conclusions about the feasibility of intracortical recordings as the basis of an effective FES user interface. The timing of our proposed two-year project is also fortuitous, for at least two reasons: (1) A new family of neuroprosthesis devices connected together by a networked design will begin human trials in a separate study within the next year, and this will also serve as the basis of an advanced neuroprosthesis for restoring arm movements to individuals with high tetraplegia (the group targeted by the proposed study) within the next several years. A high-performance intracortical interface could be easily interfaced with this advanced neuroprosthesis to complete a breakthrough rehabilitation treatment for these individuals. (2) The development of a fully implanted neural recording system is also approaching human deployment, which would alleviate concerns with combining an implanted FES system with a percutaneous BCI system, while also completing the long-standing goal of deploying a completely implanted, BCI-controlled FES system for restoring arm movements. The results of the proposed two-year project will thus provide critical information on the command and control algorithms needed to complete a fully implanted, BCI-controlled FES system that reanimates the arm and hand of individuals with complete paralysis.
 Over the next two years, we will further develop signal processing and decoder techniques that use multiple signal modalities to increase the robustness of control and can take into account the non-stationarities associated with cortical control. We will complete the development of a real-time, 11 DOF Dynamic Arm Simulator, and continue to develop computer-based visualizations that are immersive and compelling enough to the participants to allow relevant evaluations of both BCI and proposed FES controller algorithms before actually implanting a real FES system. We will explore several fundamental properties of our intracortical interface using these methods, including (1) determining how many arm DOF can be simultaneously controlled in a continuous manner and which coordinate frame (joint vs. Cartesian) is optimal for intracortical control, (2) evaluating the use of goal-based decoding as a way to reduce the cognitive burden on the participant, (3) examining the feasibility of controlling functional hand grasp and wrist movements to perform standard activities of daily living hand via the same BrainGate2 systems used for control of the rest of the upper extremity, and (4) testing the ability of these same intracortical recordings to effectively control tasks where the user must produce forces rather than movements, and/or interact with objects that have their own mechanical dynamics. At the conclusion of this study, we will have acquired significant information that will guide the direction of the field (and our own research activities) for several years to come.

column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM. column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

 1. Project Planning: Participate in internal planning calls and meetings to ensure all project activities are well coordinated, effective and continuously improving. 
 2. Hospital-level Support: Coaching for improvement at the hospital level through awareness and sharing of best practices; site visits with express preparation and understanding of current data reporting and cultural challenges; any solicited ad hoc improvement needs must be met.
 3. Data Collection: Support hospital-level data collection through integration into topic and role based education; promotion of CDS; alignment with measure reporting requirements; strive to customize support for hospitals based on relevant national, state and hospital data reporting levels.
 4. Clinical Education Support: Support topic and role groups, including but not limited to leading and developing educational trainings at the state level.  Align with and provide any needed clinical support to the programming, led by HRET partners at the national level, including identifying hospital speakers. Support overall alignment with strategic goals of HIIN and reinforce through education and training.
 5. Engagement: Support HIIN LISTSERVs through sharing questions and contributing to conversations which match staff expertise; promote HRET HIIN website content by contributing peer-shared resources and relevant education materials to be a strong resource and encourage sustainability for HIIN hospitals. Provide feedback to national team on needed resources based on hospital conversations. Engage in partnerships with QIN-QIOs, TCPI and other identified partners in support of hospital improvement in HIIN.
 6. CMS Deliverable Support: Provide necessary documentation and sufficient detail to support the HRET deliverables to the funder, CMS. This includes monthly, midyear and annual reports, and also any ad hoc requests from CMS.
 7. Financial: Provide documentation required by HRET staff to document activities engaged in by state partner staff and submit invoices to HRET in the provided format. If pre-approved in writing by HRET for travel, submit timely travel reimbursement forms and supporting documentation abiding by the HRET Subcontractor Expense Reimbursement Guidelines and subject to federal rates of reimbursement for staff and contractors. For Milestone 1, CMS strongly discourages the use of monetary incentives for hospitals  participation.  The Milestone 1 payment is funds for data related support for the hospitals to use to support new data collection efforts that align with the HIIN topics. The Milestone 1 payment will not be used to incent hospitals to participate, nor will the funds be unduly withheld from the hospitals.
 8. Compliance: Ensure that all aspects of compliance related to this Agreement are adhered to including but not limited to the Flowdown Provisions.
 
   Deliverables - Subcontractor will do as follows and provide the following deliverables at the following times:
 
 Service Deliverable Delivery Date
 Service 1: Project Planning 1. Support the HRET HIIN network alignment by participation in the weekly state partner call; one call per week.  Weekly throughout the project
  2. Provide staff and leadership to participate in each of the biweekly, one state partner check-in calls with HRET HIIN state lead, data lead and improvement advisor (state partner triad). Biweekly for the duration of the project
  3. Support project planning and success through attendance and participation by at least one state partner lead in the twice a year state partner convenings. At least two, times annually throughout the project
 Service 2: Hospital-level Support 1. Through recruitment efforts, approach and engage all acute, critical access and children s hospitals dedicated to the HIIN project goals; collect and document to HRET the receipt of hospital commitment letter; ensure the completion of the Needs Assessment. Commitment Letter by December 16, 2016
 
 Needs Assessment by January 31, 2017
  2. Conduct informed site visits with each committed hospital, at least once; complete post-site visit form for each visit. Initial Visit by March 31, 2017 and as needed
 Service 3: Data Collection 1. Ensure at least 70% of eligible hospitals are reporting on applicable 15 of the 17 CMS-required measures, monthly.  Monthly for the duration of the project
  2. Support monthly hospital submission of data into CDS: either by coaching and facilitation or through shell upload of state data to CDS. 
  3. Support submission of hospital-level operational metric data; ensure accuracy of hospital measure selection for all required measures.  
 Service 4: Clinical Education Support 1. Develop state and/or hospital level clinical education activity action items based on relevant national, state and hospital data reporting levels; support hospital-level data collection, promotion of CDS, alignment with measure reporting requirements on calls, meetings and virtual events. Monthly for the duration of the project
 Service 5: Engagement 1. Submit documentation in CMS monthly report about hospital-level contact and feedback, including but not limited to: in-person meetings, site visits and coaching calls.  Monthly
  2. Engage with QINs-QIOs, TCPI and other partners as needed in support of hospitals. Submit documentation about partnership in CMS monthly report. 
 Service 6: CMS Deliverable Support 1. Ensure timely and sufficient information is submitted for each CMS Monthly Report.  Monthly for the duration of the project
  2. Support HRET in the submission of the Midyear Report to CMS. Base Year 1: March 16, 2017
 Base Year 2: March 16, 2018
  3. Support HRET in the submission of the special report on interim target attainment. Prior to September 14, 2017
  4. Support HRET in the submission of the draft final to CMS. Prior to August 10, 2018
  5. Support HRET in the submission of the Final Report to CMS. Prior to September 4, 2018
  6. Support HRET in the submission of other contract deliverables as necessary. HRET will provide the information for the necessary support for the deliverable at least two weeks in advance of the deliverable deadline. As needed for the duration of the project
 Service 7: Financial 1. Submit monthly invoices on the 15th day of each calendar month for the prior month to HIINFinance@aha.org detailing activities engaged in by state partner staff and support. If that date falls on a Saturday, Sunday or holiday, the next business day will substitute. Monthly for the duration of the project
  2. Submit travel reimbursement forms and supporting documentation for travel that was pre-approved in writing by the HRET HIIN team within five business days of travel completion, as necessary. Monthly for the duration of the project

column43: IGF::OT::IGF B CELL EPITOPE DISCOVERY AND MECHANISMS OF ANTIBODY PROTECTION
column67: Contracts and Grants,Educational Institution,Nonprofit Organization,Private University or College,Veterinary College
column76: The proposed work is divided into four tasks. Task 1 - Epitome Identification, The goal of Task 1 is to generate comprehensive, high-Resolution B cell epitome maps of RTA and RTB, with particular emphasis on discontinuous epitopes. Task 2-Epitope validation, The goal of Task 2 is to classify the B cell epitopes identified on RTA and RTB in Task 1 as being functional targets of toxin0neutralizing, non neutralizing or possibly even toxin-enhancing antibodies and to then determine, in the context of a polyclonal antibody response, their relative contributions to eliciting antibodies involved in protective immunity to ricin. Task 3- Data management and Epitope Submission, Submission of epitopes to IEDB.  All immunological data generated unto this contract will be maintained at local collaborating institutions and sent to the Wadsworth Center for centralized storage. Submission of structure to PDB. Within six months of completion of ricin toxin B cell epitope verification and validation the Mantis laboratory will be responsible submitting detailed epitopes and related information to the IEDB. Task 4- Mechanisms of Antibody Protection, The goal of task 4 is to determine in detail the mechanisms by which murine mAbs and VHH identified and validated in Task 1 and 2  neutralize ricin, in vitro and in vivo.

column76: The Subcontractor shall conduct research, analysis, and technical support on a quick-turnaround and longer-lead basis. EE topics of relevance include:  EE policy types, experience and impacts; EE potential by state, by sector, by year, and by potential type; EE program portfolio development and implementation; EE policy costs and cost analysis; EE policy impact on power system including costs, reduced energy and demand, and utility regulatory effects; projections of EE policy impacts and costs; evaluation, measurement, verification (EM&V) of EE policy impacts.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF: CDRH MEDICAL DEVICE CYBERSECURITY STRATEGIC SUPPORT
column45: ALL OTHER PROFESSIONAL, SCIENTIFIC, AND TECHNICAL SERVICES
column76:
The scope of this effort is to establish a collaboration between MITRE and the Massachusetts General Hospital/Partners Healthcare Medical Device Plug and Play (MD PnP) Lab to create the medical device cybersecurity testbed necessary to support FDA CDRH s objectives for medical device cyber security preparedness and response. 
 
 In addition, the scope includes hosting a WannaCry healthcare regional stakeholder meeting and provide input to the meeting's design. Outcomes associated with this task: 
   A realistic, biomedical environment that supports both preparedness exercises and live cyber-physical incident response activities, with the capability to test solutions in real time without potentially affecting clinical care.
   The ability to test and validate vulnerabilities, mitigation strategies, and cyber resilient, clinical configurations that enable continued clinical operation in the face of cyber-physical hazards, in collaboration with MITRE SMEs, in support of local, regional, and national preparedness goals.
   The identification of medical device vulnerabilities, vetted mitigation strategies, and cyber resilient configurations, in collaboration with MITRE SMEs, in direct support of the FDA s postmarket guidance policy calling for greater transparency, adoption of coordinated vulnerability disclosures, and sharing medical device cybersecurity information.

column43: TAS::75 0850::TAS RECOVERY ACT - TISSUE SOURCE SITE (TSS) NETWORKS IN SUPPORT OF THE CANCER GENOME ATLAS (TCGA) PROGRAM
column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

column76:
CMS seeks to employ an enterprise-wide organizational improvement strategy that aligns resources and drives results in
 meeting strategic objectives and achieving agency priorities. Toward that end, MITRE will provide independent advice,
 guidance, and expertise in organizational change management, process improvement (e.g., Lean, Agile), and other areas of
 expertise to guide and support the agency s efforts and program improvement projects. MITRE will develop and implement a
 CMS-specific framework for improvement and a strategy for integrating it into CMS business processes and the
 organizational culture.
 Task Description
 The Contractor will provide expertise in Lean thinking and management systems to support the development of the CMSspecific
 framework for improvement. The Contractor s work will include (but is not limited to) developing the Lean
 transformation model, including the management system, human development system, and improvement system.

This agreement (this  Modification ) modifies the HRET Subcontract Agreement ( Agreement ) between the Health Research & Educational Trust ("Contractor" or "HRET") and the Massachusetts Hospital Research and Education Association (MHREA) ("Subcontractor"). Contractor and Subcontractor are each a "Party" and collectively are the "Parties." Terms used in this Modification will have the meanings given to them in the Agreement unless otherwise defined below.  The efforts of Subcontractor under the Agreement as modified by this Modification will support the Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2016-00067C ("Prime Contract ), dated September 28, 2016, issued by The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ("CMS").  
 
 This Modification replaces the following items:
 
 1. The purpose of this modification is to split the current 12 month option period into a 3 month Option Period 1 (has been exercised) and a 9 month Option Period 2 (if exercised).   
 Description Period of Performance
 Option Period 1 3/28/2019-6/27/2019
 Option Period 2 6/28/2019-3/27/2020
 
 2. The existing Total Initial Two-Year Budget Amount has expired. The Option Period 1 Budget Amount, representing activity from March 28, 2019- June 27, 2019, which is based on the number of Committed Hospitals.  The Authorized Payment Amounts Schedule is included, and supersedes any previous authorized payment amounts schedule.  
 
 3. SECTION I - CONTRACT CLAUSES
 I.1 CLAUSES INCORPORATED BY REFERENCE FAR 52.217-9 (MAR 2000), is modified to read:
 (a) The Government may extend the term of this contract by written notice to the Contractor
 within 7 days provided that the Government gives the Contractor a preliminary written notice of its intent to extend at least 15 days before the contract expires. The preliminary notice does not
 commit the Government to an extension.
 (b) If the Government exercises this option, the extended contract shall be considered to
 include this option clause.
 (c) The total duration of this contract, including the exercise of any options under this clause,
 shall not exceed 42 months.
 
 Notwithstanding the foregoing, if the Government timely exercises Option Period 2 and HRET chooses to extend this Subcontract as a result, HRET shall give Subcontractor written notice 6 days prior to the end of Option Period 1.  This subcontract will then be updated to reflect the economic terms and scope of work for Option Period 2.
 
 ALL OTHER TERMS AND CONDITIONS OF THIS CONTRACT REMAIN UNCHANGED.
 Other than as expressly set out in this Modification, nothing in this Modification is intended to alter the rights, duties and obligations of the Parties under the Agreement, which shall remain in full force and effect as expressly modified hereby.  This Modification may be executed by the Parties in separate counterparts and each counterpart shall be deemed to be an original, but all such counterparts together shall constitute one and the same instrument. 
 
 
 IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Modification.

ARTICLE 2 - PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE The period of performance for the accomplishment of the work herein shall be from 10/01/2013 to 09/30/2016. Compensation is payable at the following rates: 3.1.1 Compensation at the fixed rate of $100.00 per hour for a not-to-exceed amount of $30,000.00. 3.2,, Invoices shall be submitted no more often than monthly. An original invoice and two (2) copies shall be submitted. The invoice must specify this Purchase Order number, the period covered by the invoice, the dates, hours and work performed therein. 3.3 The Contractor shall be compensated for actual services performed. The rate of compensation in Article 3.1 is considered to be a fixed rate for the period of time identified in Article 2, or for one (1) year from the commencement date, whichever is later. 3.4 MIT shall not be obligated to pay the Contractor any amount in excess of the total amount set forth in Article 3.1. Costs in excess of this amount will be incurred at the Contractor's sole liability. Authorization to increase the total amount must be in writing duly signed by the agent who signs this contract or an authorized representative. Should actual costs incurred be less than the not-to-exceed amount, the Purchase Order shall be reduced accordingly. ARTICLE 4 - MIT REPRESENTATIVES 4.1 The MIT Technical Representative for all work under this contract is: Center for Biomedical Intervention Sloan School of Management Massachusetts Institute of Technology Building E38-659 Cambridge, MA 02139 The person named above is responsible for determining the acceptability of work performed and items delivered. Questions of a technical nature should be directed to the person named above. 4.2 The MIT Administrative Representative for this contract is: Christina T. Lo Senior Contract Administrator Massachusetts Institute of Technology Building NE49-4122 Cambridge, MA 02139 Tel: (617) 253-1747 Questions of a contractual nature should be directed to the person named above. ARTICLE 5 - EMPLOYMENT STATUS 5.1 At all times during the term of this agreement, the Contractor shall be an independent contractor of MIT and shall not, under any circumstances, be deemed to be an employee or agent of MIT, and shall not be entitled to participate in any employee benefit plans or employee programs of MIT. Nothing contained within this Agreement shall be deemed or construed to create a partnership or joint venture, to create the relationship of employee/employer, principal/agent, or otherwise to create any liability whatsoever between the Contractor and MIT in any capacity other than as parties to this agreement. 5.2 The Contractor certifies that: ,,1. the Contractor is free from control and direction in connection with the performance of this service, both under his contract for the performance of service and in fact; and ,,2. the service is performed outside the usual course of business of the employer; and ,,3. the Contractor is customarily engaged in an independently established trade, occupation, profession, or business of the same nature as that involved in the service performed. column43: NATIONAL IMPLEMENTATION OF COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CATHETER-ASSOCIATED URINARY TRACT INFECTION (CAUTI)
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE SOCIAL SCIENCES AND HUMANITIES
column76:
Scope of Work 
 
 In August 2011, AHRQ sought to deploy and implement a program for the support and expansion of the adoption and use of a CUSP that can be applied to reduce CAUTI in hospitals in all States, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico through State-based or regional consortia/collaborative in a phased approach.  This work builds upon and expands the current activities to demonstrate the effectiveness of CUSP for CAUTI in twelve States.  This follow-on effort utilizes the resources and materials for CUSP for CAUTI that have been developed as part of earlier contract work for this expansion of the national implementation effort.  
 
 The total funding for Subcontractor s effort is $20,000 U.S. Dollars in the Base Year and $50,000 in the Option Year. Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the following tasks and deliverables in excess of this amount.  
 
 TASKS:
 
 1. Ensure the recruitment and continued active participation of at least 10 hospitals in the project.
 2. Obtain and maintain general knowledge of the project (goals, expectations, interventions, timelines, schedules, etc.) and serve as a liaison between the national project team and hospital units.
 3. Work with unit teams to assist with culture improvements and overcoming project barriers.
 4. Provide individual coaching with identified high outliers.
 5. Regularly participate in scheduled calls with the national project team and encourage participating hospitals to do the same.
 6. Work with extended faculty to develop specific state curriculum needs.
 7. Commit to the goal of reducing mean CAUTI rates in participating clinical units by 25 percent, and improving safety culture as evidenced by improved teamwork and communication by employing CUSP methodology.  
 
 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Provide a part-time project coordinator to function as the state lead.
 2. Monitor and coordinate with participating hospitals to assure their submission of:
 a. Monthly infection rate data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 b. AHRQ Safety Culture surveys at the beginning and end of the project
 c. Quarterly team check up tool data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 3. Submit the State Lead Monthly Status Report (Attachment E).
 4. Facilitate monthly coaching calls and establish agendas for them.
 5. Coordinate three face-to-face learning sessions (at the start of the project, at mid-collaborative, and at the end of the collaborative).
 6. Coordinate site visits to units as needed.

Building on prior research, all of the Medicare claims-based analyses for the project will be based in the
 Department of Health Care Policy at Harvard Medical School. Dr. Haiden Huskamp will serve as site Pl,
 overseeing all phases of the work at Harvard, in addition to being involved in other aspects of the
 project. As detailed in the project's management plan, Ors. Huskamp and Stevenson will continue their
 collaboration on hospice-related topics in the context of this project and will be in regular contact
 throughout the project period. Ms. Laurie Meneades will serve as the programmer at Harvard, also
 building off of her prior work in using the required Medicare datasets.
 The primary analytic tasks that will occur at Harvard under the direction of Dr. Huskamp center around
 the integration of the hospice ownership coding conducted by Dr. Stevenson and his team at Vanderbilt
 with the following administrative datasets: the Medicare Beneficiary Summary File; the Nursing Home
 Minimum Data Set; and Medicare hospice claims. The analyses will utilize these datasets from 2004
 through the most recent year of available data. Dr. Huskamp will also participate in the writing of
 reports summarizing key findings from the project.
