column76:
Severable Options:
 Option 3: 0258-0597-4609
 Option 4: 0258-0632-4609
 Option 5: 0258-0657-4609
 
 Our mandate as a part of the Center for Research on Influenza Pathogenesis will be pandemic preparedness through addition to the current body of knowledge on influenza virus pathogenesis, host restriction, ecology and natural history, transmission, evolution and host adaptation, interactions between influenza virus proteins and gene segments, evasion of immunity, and induction of host responses by conducting novel research aimed at publication in peer-reviewed journals. Specifically, we will undertake the following tasks: 
 
 PROJECT.  Surveillance and Surveillance-related Research on Viral Disease Ecology, Evolution and Adaptation, and Transmission/Pathogenesis at the Avian/Mammal and Human/Animal interface.
 
 1) Carry out influenza virologic, epidemiologic and disease surveillance with an emphasis on rapid characterization of influenza viruses.
 
 2) Determine the natural history of influenza virus and role for wild birds in the spread of influenza virus.
 
 3) Investigate the viral and host determinants of viral transmission from avian to mammalian species and their emergence in the wild.
 
 4) Deliverables
 a. Characterized viral isolates and reverse genetics viral constructs.
 b. Animal and environmental viral sample and analysis data and metadata.
 c. Animal serology data and metadata.
 d. Full genome sequence of targeted and selected significant viral isolates and samples.
 e. Research publications, progress reports and final report.
 f. Active participation in Network surveillance-related activities.
 g. Active response to pandemic surveillance needs.
 
 
 For Non-Severable Option 18C   Pilot Project (0258-0576-4609)
 
 Tasks
 1. Influenza Sequencing Core Related Work
 a. Tufts University shall continue research studies to develop and establish a sequencing methodology for single particle viral sequencing to be implemented in CEIRS DIGS. 
 b. Tufts University shall contribute expertise and consultation where possible to develop the overall project sequencing capability.
 
 2. Influenza pandemic surveillance
 a. Tufts University shall expand influenza surveillance capacity to detect and isolate virus with pandemic potential, particularly H5Nx and related virus.
 
 Deliverables
 a. Repository of animal influenza viruses and associated metadata.
 b. Publications
 c. Progress and final reports
 
 Option 11A - Equitable Adjustment - 400 Animal Samples (0258-0647-4609)
 
 Project. Enhanced Alaska surveillance of wild reservoirs. 
 Alaska is situated at the crest of the Pacific Rim and is a known 'hybrid zone' for the exchange of virus from East Asia and North America owing to the mass migration of breeding birds. We will leverage our continued Alaskan surveillance to build a model for forecasting inter-continental introduction and identifying host populations at high risk of infection from introduced strains through the following activities:
 
 1) Carry out enhanced Influenza virologic, epidemlologic and disease surveillance with an emphasis on rapid characterization of influenza viruses: 
 a. Detect HPAI viruses, viral segments, or their derivatives in Alaskan wild bird populations. 
 b. Obtain viral isolates and/or sequence to enable continued genotypic and phenotypic evaluation of circulating influenza with pandemic potential. 
 
 2) Assess whether prior exposure to low pathogenic subtypes suggests cross-immunity to currently circulating H5 clade 2.3.4.4.
 a. Assemble pseudovirus for serological screening with representative H5 hemagglutinin.
 b. Assess antigenic distance between circulating H5 clade 2.3.4.4 viruses
 c. Model the risk of inter-continental transmission of H5 viruses into Alaska.
 
 3) Deliverables
 a. Characterized virus samples from wild avian reservoir species.
 b. Full genome sequence of targeted and selected significant viral isolates and samples.
 c. Pseudotype virus constructs for antigenic testing
 d. Research publication, progress reports and final report.

column43: PROGRAM SUPPORT, ANALYSIS, AND ADVANCEMENT OF OTAQ'S TRANSPORTATION EMISSION REDUCTION AND FUEL SAVINGS PROGRAMS
column45: ADMINISTRATIVE MANAGEMENT AND GENERAL MANAGEMENT CONSULTING SERVICES
column76:
TASK 1: TEAM and GHG Planning Technical Assistance and Case Studies
 EPA s Travel Efficiency Assessment Method (TEAM) is a method for estimating transportation emission reductions that relies on sketch-analysis of travel impacts in conjunction with the MOVES emission factor model. EPA has applied the TEAM approach in a number of cities to date, relying on the TRIMMS model developed by the Center for Urban Transportation Research (CUTR) at the University of South Florida to estimate travel impacts. The objective of this task is to assist three additional areas in applying the TEAM approach to either a transportation emission reduction or a GHG planning analysis including inventory development and assessment of ability to meet future reduction targets. 
 
 TASK 2: Update EPA Report: Methodologies for Estimating Emissions and Travel Activity Effects of TCMs
 The objective of this task is to make recommendations for updating EPA s 1994 document, Methodologies for Estimating Emissions and Travel Activity Effects of TCMs.  The 1994 document includes six types of TCMs: telecommuting, flextime, compressed work weeks, ridesharing, and parking management. The document provides equations for determining changes in vehicle-trips and VMT considering factors such as the market size, average vehicle occupancy, travel behavior prior to change, trip lengths, days per week, peak period fractions, etc. The section on emission factor development describes the use of the MOBILE1 model. It also describes a process for analyzing a package of TCM strategies; case studies; and a summary of TCM methods developed in California.
 
 TASK 3: Comparison of Transportation Sketch Models
 A 2011 EPA report, Potential Changes in Emissions Due to Improvements in Travel Efficiency, identifies nine sketch models or spreadsheet-based tools. It can be difficult to do  apples to apples  comparisons between tools because different tools include different strategies or specify inputs in different ways. Therefore, a comparison of selected tools would be extremely enlightening and helpful for agencies in understanding their options for analysis methods, as well as for researchers in further developing robust tools and methods.

column43: NATIONAL IMPLEMENTATION OF COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CATHETER-ASSOCIATED URINARY TRACT INFECTION (CAUTI)
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE SOCIAL SCIENCES AND HUMANITIES
column76:
Scope of Work 
 
 In August 2011, AHRQ sought to deploy and implement a program for the support and expansion of the adoption and use of a CUSP that can be applied to reduce CAUTI in hospitals in all States, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico through State-based or regional consortia/collaborative in a phased approach.  This work builds upon and expands the current activities to demonstrate the effectiveness of CUSP for CAUTI in twelve States.  This follow-on effort utilizes the resources and materials for CUSP for CAUTI that have been developed as part of earlier contract work for this expansion of the national implementation effort.  
 
 The total funding for Subcontractor s effort is $20,000 U.S. Dollars in the Base Year and $50,000 in the Option Year. Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the following tasks and deliverables in excess of this amount.  
 
 TASKS:
 
 1. Ensure the recruitment and continued active participation of at least 10 hospitals in the project.
 2. Obtain and maintain general knowledge of the project (goals, expectations, interventions, timelines, schedules, etc.) and serve as a liaison between the national project team and hospital units.
 3. Work with unit teams to assist with culture improvements and overcoming project barriers.
 4. Provide individual coaching with identified high outliers.
 5. Regularly participate in scheduled calls with the national project team and encourage participating hospitals to do the same.
 6. Work with extended faculty to develop specific state curriculum needs.
 7. Commit to the goal of reducing mean CAUTI rates in participating clinical units by 25 percent, and improving safety culture as evidenced by improved teamwork and communication by employing CUSP methodology.  
 
 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Provide a part-time project coordinator to function as the state lead.
 2. Monitor and coordinate with participating hospitals to assure their submission of:
 a. Monthly infection rate data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 b. AHRQ Safety Culture surveys at the beginning and end of the project
 c. Quarterly team check up tool data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 3. Submit the State Lead Monthly Status Report (Attachment E).
 4. Facilitate monthly coaching calls and establish agendas for them.
 5. Coordinate three face-to-face learning sessions (at the start of the project, at mid-collaborative, and at the end of the collaborative).
 6. Coordinate site visits to units as needed.

Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ). During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters. MITRE seeks subject matter expertise to support the research, design, and development of a new Merit-Based
 Incentive Payment System for CMS. MITRE seeks subject matter expertise in:
   Health care payment systems. Required expertise includes health payment systems design, process
 improvement, performance transformation of health care departments and agencies, health
 economics, and financial strategies.
   Health care analytics. Required expertise includes retrospective claims data analysis, model design,
 and model simulation.
   Health care policy research and analysis. Required expertise includes health care policy research
 and analysis.

Task 1: Task Administration
 Task administration activities will be coordinated by the MITRE Project Leader, with input from Contractor. The Contractor shall: 
 1. Participate in meetings and contribute to progress reports throughout the duration of this project, as needed to communicate status, key issues, and findings to CMS.  
 2. Contribute to developing and maintaining a current Project Work Plan, including a detailed timeline of project milestones and deliverables.
 3. Provide a monthly financial report that includes, (1) Inception To Date (ITD) actual costs for work performed (ACWP) for the project, (2) and the contractor s best estimate of the time-phased resources required to complete the remaining authorized work   the Estimate at Complete (EAC).
 4. Invoice MITRE monthly for allowable incurred costs.
 
 Task 2: Lean Expert Consultation
 Provide consultation to MITRE, ThedaCare Center for Healthcare Value and CMS regarding organization-wide approaches to design a lean management system to support the requirements of CMS  operating environment. Attendance of two Senior Lean experts to participate in the CMS Strategy Session for Lean Transformation activities from 31 May-June 3, 2016. John O Donnell and Darlene Dumont are considered key persons identified to participate.

column76:
Dr. Spite will provide liquid-chromatagraphy/tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) services as a 
 subcontractor in support of Stage B VITA, entitled  Prevention of anastomotic intimal hyperplasia 
 by a resolvin-eluting perivascular device . Collaboration on this project is completely feasible 
 given preliminary data and state-of-the-art lipidomics platform. As you know from our extensive 
 ongoing collaborations, we have expertise with LC-MS/MS analysis of lipid mediators and have 
 instrumentation (AB Sciex Qtrap 5500) that enables the identification and sensitive quantification 
 of lipid mediators in biological matrices.
 
 In line with stipulated Milestones, we will perform analysis to validate the structural integrity 
 and concentration of the resolvin D1 (RvD1) analog, benzo-diacetylenic-17R-RvD1 methyl ester 
 (BDA-RvD1) in samples. I will also provide scientific consultation on an ad hoc basis as part of 
 this program.
 Milestone 1: Device optimization-testing for active compound stability
 Milestone 2:  Non-GLP efficacy study, ovine model
 Milestone 3: GLP efficacy study, ovine model

The Subcontractor will provide support to EPA in the four work areas described below, which fall under
 the responsibility of the programs in the Climate Protection Partnerships Division. The Subcontractor will
 track and report hours and expenditures for each of the four individual tasks.
 Note that Task 1 is reserved for ERG administrative activities in the original EPA Task Order. Thus, the
 numbering below starts with Task 2.
 Task 2: AVERT and User Manual Updates and Maintenance
 Under the new Task Order, the Subcontractor should be prepared to conduct the steps described below if
 directed by EPA.
 Respond to state beta tester comments. In the fourth quarter of 2013, AVERT and user guidance
 materials were delivered to five state environmental agencies for review and a  beta test.  The
 Subcontractor will finish characterizing the comments in consultation with EPA, respond to open
 questions as required, and modify both AVERT and guidance materials as deemed appropriate, with EPA
 guidance. The bulk of this work is expected to occur immediately upon issuance of the Task Order to
 support the release of AVERT in early 2014.
 Finalize benchmarking analysis. A benchmarking analysis was developed under a previous Task Order.
 The Subcontractor will respond to EPA comments and finalize the benchmarking analysis accordingly,
 and will work with EPA to provide technical support during the internal/external release of this document
 as deemed appropriate. As needed and under the direction of EPA, the Subcontractor will modify
 components of the tool to address findings from the benchmarking analysis

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month. column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

Building on prior research, all of the Medicare claims-based analyses for the project will be based
 in the Department of Health Care Policy at Harvard Medical School. Dr. Haiden Huskamp will
 serve as site PI, overseeing all phases of the work at Harvard, in addition to being involved in
 other aspects of the project. As detailed in the project's management plan, Ors. Huskamp and
 Stevenson, who have collaborated on research related to utilization of medications, long-term care
 services, and hospice and palliative care for over a decade, will be in regular contact throughout
 the project period. Ms. Laurie Meneades will serve at the programmer at Harvard, also building

column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

 FIRST AMENDMENT TO ORIGINAL SUBCONTRACT
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 This is the first Amendment to the Subcontract entered into on the 71
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 day of January 2016, by
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 and between the Institute for Healthcare Improvement ("Subcontractor"), with offices at 20
 University Road, Cambridge, MA 02138, and the Health Research & Educational Trust
 ("HRET"), with offices at 155 N. Wacker Drive, Chicago, IL 60606.
 
 The purpose of this amendment is to exercise the Option Year 3 of the subcontract  for the period 
 of September 30, 2015 through September 29, 2016. The total funding for Subcontractor's effort 
 within the AHRQ Safety Program for Ambulatory Surgery in the Performance Period is ($106,487 U.S. 
 Dollars).
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property: The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor plans 
 to use and/or deliver the following pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights in its performance of 
 this Agreement:
     NONE
 
 Key Personnel: The following individual/positions are designated as key personnel under this
 Agreement:
    Dr. Kedar Mate, Senior Sponsor
    Lindsay Martin, MPH, Executive Director
    JeffRakover, MPA, Research Assistant
    TBD, Project Manager
    Kevin Little, PhD., Improvement Advisor
    Richard Scoville, PhD., Improvement Advisor
 
 Scope of Work: Working under the direction ofHRET Project Director, Stephen Hines, as a 
 subcontractor to HRET's contract from the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) 
 HHSA290201000025I Task Order #5 "AHRQ's Safety Program for Ambulatory Surgery", The Institute for 
 Healthcare Improvement will assist HRET in the  implementation of the AHRQ SUSP Ambulatory Surgery 
 national project through providing expert input into the design of the improvement & evaluation 
 strategies & activities for HRET.
 
 Tasks:
 The current thinking around sustainability of quality and safety improvement initiatives emphasizes 
 the following five steps to improving sustainability: selecting changes that have achieved 
 performance thresholds that should be sustained, predicting their "stickiness," developing the 
 infrastructure for sustainability, continuous ongoing measurement, and making changes to support 
 systems that will improve likelihood of sustaining the gains.
 
 
 
 
 Transforming health care through research and education www.hret.org       155 North Wacker     tel 
 312 422 2600
 Chicago, tl60606     fax 312 422 4568
 
 
 
 
 
 HRHEALTHERESEATRCH &
 EDUCATIONAL TRUST
 In Partnership with AHA
 
 Step One: Determine that a change has achieved acceptable levels of capability and reliability
 IHI will work with the 5-6 initial sites to determine which changes are to be sustained. The 
 desired changes are those which have reached adequate levels of capability and reliability. 
 Capability means that the change is producing the desired impact on patients or populations, and 
 reliability means that the change is consistently producing this level of impact. If a change has 
 not succeeded in reaching the levels of performance that you hope for your system, focusing on 
 sustainability will result in sustaining subpar performance. Conversely, when you have succeeded in 
 optimizing your system through a series of tests to adapt the changes, and these are reliably being 
 performed, a focus on sustainability will be important.  This first step will identify the changes 
 that are ready to be sustained.
 
 Step Two: Develop and use a sustainability prediction tool to understand the nature of the change 
 and context
 Once the changes for sustaining are identified, IHI will work with the initial sites to apply a
 sustainability prediction tool. Predicting sustainability yields quantifiable, actionable 
 information as to the likelihood that a change will stick in the system, identify opportunities to 
 improve its "stickiness," or to improve the receptivity of the context. The NHS Sustainability 
 Model is the most widely known and used sustainability prediction tool. This tool captures the 
 essence of the key attributes of both the change and its context. Some minor customization and adap 
 ation to
 the Ambulatory Surgery project and context will be needed.
 
 · Once the IHI team makes these changes, the initial teams will use the tool and the information it 
 yields to strengthen areas of weakness in the change or context that are diagnosed through this 
 process. This tool is really meant as a way of beginning an important dialogue amongst the teams at 
 the surgery centers.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 't·
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 Step Three: Develop the infrastructure for sustainability
 SustainabilitY. is the province of leaders at all levels in an organization. Developing the 
 infrastructure for sustainability requires developing the standard work for leaders particularly 
 those leading clinical microsystems (front-line service delivery units). Effective standard work of 
 leaders includes the following six elements:
 
   Standardization. Processes to define & disseminate standard work: what to do and how to do it. 
 Having well-defined daily, weekly, monthly, quarterlyd annual tasks (i.e., clearly defined standard 
 work) related to the particular change at hand. The supervisor has a clear sense of these tasks, 
 regardless of how they are outlined (in a daily checklist, a huddle board and huddle agenda, etc.).
 
   Accountability. Process to review execution of leader standard work. The organization has systems 
 to monitor whether staff are implementing standard work. This is crucial to maintaining process 
 control, understanding what training needs may exist, or to uncover processes that do not work 
 well. Managers use this information as the basis for

 improvement of the work unit; evaluation of individual staff performance for promotion or 
 separation is secondary.
 
   Visual Management. Systems provide information to regulate current period performance in a visual 
 way with attendant daily communication system to ensure that all key staff are aware of mission 
 critical issues and take appropriate actions in their day. The unit has information to monitor the 
 performance of existing processes. Most often, clinical units track such information using visual 
 metric boards, displayed publicly or semi-publicly, that show key indicators which in tum align 
 with system-wide strategic goals. These visual metric boards are usually accompany by some form of 
 daily communication process, often in the form of a daily huddle with all team members, to ensure 
 everyone understands the mission ofthe unit and the key points of vulnerability to heighten 
 awareness and sensitivity of all staff.
 
   Methods for Problem-Solving. Methods for problems solvable at the frontline and skill in 
 improvement methods. Supervisors and frontline staff have methods available to solve problems as 
 they arise. For example, they use versions of root cause analysis and Plan-Do  Study-Act cycles to 
 solve problems. A3 is a popular Lean tool for this driver. Frontline supervisors and staff are 
 skilled in these tools and methods-with experts available to provide support as necessary.
 
   Channels for Escalation. Frontline staff identify & escalate issues that require management 
 intervention to resolve, either directly or through commission of a formal improvement project. Not 
 all problems are readily solvable at the frontline. A well  functioning management system includes 
 clear protocols to distinguish problems that should be escalated to higher tiers, and those that 
 may require dedicated improvement initiatives.
 
   Integration of Standard Work. Goals and standard work are integrated across
 organiz ;ttionallevels. Frontline leader standard work must be well-integrated with frontline 
 clinical standard work. And it must be nested and well-integrated up and down the leadership chain 
 within an organization in order to be continuously reinforced and supported.  In addition, by 
 ensuring integration above and below, the standard work of
 front-line leaders ultimately ensures alignment of all quality activities with the original
 organizational purpose.
 
 Step Four: Continuous ongoing control measurement of the change
 A vital behavior in sustainability is continuous control measurement to ensure that the process
 remains stable over time. Infrastructure and responsibility for this key activity should be built 
 into the leaders' standard work and the usual operations of the service unit. Some mechanism of 
 regular review of control measurement should be created and automatic trigger thresholds set to 
 alert observers to evidence for when a process/change fall beyond the control limits suggesting 
 that it is no longer being sustained.

 Step Five: Change the relevant support systems
 To sustain some changes will require changes to human resources including workforce composition or 
 role definition (job descriptions), information systems (how they are used, what data & reports are 
 produced, review procedures etc.), and potentially to long-term financing. During the steps 
 described above, these changes will hopefully become evident and can be built into the 
 sustainability plan and approach.

column76: The National Collegiate Inventors and Innovators Alliance (d/b/a  VentureWell ) is a national nonprofit organization with two decades of experience fostering scientific and technological innovation and entrepreneurship (I&E) by working with faculty institutions and students in higher education. Throughout its history, VentureWell has been committed to supporting high-impact experiential learning activities that increase the acquisition and retention of I&E concepts. Since 1995 we have engaged a community of faculty and their institutions by convening conferences, hosting trainings and developing a national network. In addition, VentureWell supports emerging student innovators and has granted more than $7.5 million in hundreds of early-stage grants that helped to launch 180 student-led ventures based on scientific and technological innovations. These companies have gone on to leverage more than $620 million in federal and private investment and now operate in 51 countries around the world. Our expertise in the field has led to our work as the implementing organization for multiple federally funded programs with strong faculty training and high participant engagement (Epicenter, I-Corps , National Innovation Network , USAID Xcelerator). VentureWell is uniquely positioned to leverage these programs and networks for implementation of the I-Corps  training for the National Institutes of Health.

column76:
Scope of Work
 Dr. Spite will provide liquid-chromatagraphy/tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) services as a subcontractor in support of Stage B VITA, entitled "Prevention of anastomotic intimal hyperplasia by a resolvin-eluting perivascular device" . Collaboration on this project is completely feasible given preliminary data and state-of-the-art lipidomics platform. As you know from our extensive ongoing collaborations, we have expertise with LC-MS/MS analysis of lipid mediators and have instrumentation (AB Sciex Otrap 5500) that enables the identification and sensitive quantification of lipid mediators in biological matrices.
 In line with stipulated Milestones, we will perform analysis to validate the structural integrity and concentration of the resolvin 01 (RvD1) analog, benzo-diacetylenic-17R-RvD1 methyl ester (BDA-RvD1) in samples.  I will also provide scientific consultation on an ad hoc basis as part of this program.
 Milestone 1: Device optimization-testing for active compound stability
 Milestone 2: Non-GLP efficacy study, ovine model
 Milestone 3: GLP efficacy study, ovine model

column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

column43: TAS::75 0850::TAS RECOVERY ACT - TISSUE SOURCE SITE (TSS) NETWORKS IN SUPPORT OF THE CANCER GENOME ATLAS (TCGA) PROGRAM
column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

column76: Conduct CDL and ADCC assays of human sera from the following experimental human viccine studies:  10 serasamples from H7N7 vaccine trial (pre- and postvaccination); 10 sera samples from H5N1 vaccine trial (pre- and post-vaccination); 5 sera samples from H7N7 LAIV/IV study (pre- and post vaccination); human mAbs to H7 (positive controls); and 3 sets of pre- and post-seasonal viccine sera and include seasonal H1 virus infected target cells in the CDL and ADCC assays.  These sera will be tested against target cells (A549) infected with wild type H7N9 strain, which is BSL3+ (alternatively could test attenuated H7N9 strains such as A/Shanghai/2/2103 generated for vaccine production, which is BSL2_).  As a positive control in the CDL and ADCC assays, target cells infected with either seasonal or 2009 pandemic H1N1 strain or a seasonal H3N2 strain will be used depending on when the serum samples were collected.

Brief summary: The overarching goal of this 5-year FDA award is to develop and implement strategies to assess, evaluate, and monitor medical countermeasure safety, performance, and patient compliance in response to a public health emergency. Clinical sites for the United States Critical Illness and Injury Trials Group Program for Emergency Preparedness (USCIITG-PREP) have been recruited to perform this work. The work is divided into a Base Period and 4 one-year Option Periods.
 Base Period (years 1-4): There are four deliverables identified for the base period:
   In year 1, develop an intravenous antiviral treatment protocol to assess the use of intravenous (IV) antivirals (e.g., IV zanamivir) under an expanded access IND for critically ill patients with confirmed influenza using electronic case report forms (eCRFs) and a data
 entry user manual.
   Utilize pre-established infrastructure for broad coverage of clinical trial sites across the
 United States
   Utilize rapid data collection tool/mechanism for collection of safety (adverse events) and
 effectiveness (performance) data
   Collaborate with BARDA and BARDA-funded company sponsors of medical countermeasures on pathway for FDA approval/licensure under the Animal Rule to meet post-marketing regulatory commitments
 The bulk of this work will be accomplished in Year 1 of the Base Period; minor iterations of
 the work are required annually thereafter. Collaborators in the USCIITG-PREP network are
 tasked with coordinating reports and completing the work required at their respective sites.
 Deliverables specific for the Base Period include:
 1. Monthly - Progress reports to include financial information and research updates, due the 15th of each month with the first report due on November 15, 2014
 2. Yearly - Progress report for the past year's work to include both research findings, financial update, and publications and speaking engagements, due November 15th of each year
 3. Yearly - Operations plan for the BARDA-sponsored phase 4 field studies, due
 September 30th of each year if applicable
 4. January 31, 2015 - Final treatment protocol for treating critically ill influenza patients with IV zanamivir
 5. July 30, 2015 - A copy of the eCRF to be used during the 2015-2016 influenza season

State Waivers under Section 1332
 The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide Subject Matter Expertise (SME) and develop template applications, waivers, and instructions for states and insurance oversight agencies to apply for state innovation waivers authorized under section 1332 of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act. The Contractor shall partner with MITRE to provide support to CMS staff during state engagements, including, but not limited to phone calls, in-person meetings, virtual meetings and webinars.
   The Contractor SMEs are required to format and develop: 
 o Guidance/Waiver Models/White papers for consumption by State Legislatures / State Department of Insurance (DOI);
 o Laying out multiple templates of possible 1332 waivers; and  
 o Engagement/Approach strategies for up to 6 States.
   The SMEs provided by the Contractor are expected to include, but not limited to senior level experts with several years of experience and extensive hands-on knowledge on 1332 waivers to produce fast turnaround templates, instructions, and engagements with states.

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.

column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

column76:
Task 1: Work Plan, Schedule, and Management
 The Subcontractor will provide a simple work plan (schedule and a few milestones) for the work described under
 Tasks 2 and 3 below. Some of the details of the work (approach, detail, etc.) will have to be worked out iteratively,
 so the Subcontractor should make and document assumptions as needed. The Subcontractor will participate in phone
 calls and email discussions with EPA and ERG as needed.
 Deliverables
   Work plan: October 31, 2013
 Task 2: Excel Tool
 The Subcontractor will create an Excel-based tool to conduct analysis similar to that done for Civil Society Institute
 study of 2011 ( Beyond BAU   ). This tool will be for internal EPA use for policy analysis/discussions and,
 likely, to support a proposal for the existing power plant GHG rule. The tool should allow for relatively easy
 scenario analysis through changes in key inputs such as cost of saved energy (program and participant), target firstyear
 savings levels, ramp-up duration/rate, start year, and perhaps one or two others identified through consultation
 with EPA. Default values should be established such that tool is immediately usable, but also can be readily updated
 as new supporting info is developed (e.g., new COSE assumptions, ramp-ups). The tool should generally be
 structured at a state level, but with consideration given to incorporation of utility data as available.

column67: 1862 Land Grant College,Contracts and Grants,Educational Institution,Nonprofit Organization,Private University or College
column76:
Base Period (0258-0509-4609)
 Option 1 (0258-0533-4609)
 Option 2 (0258-0565-4609)
 Option 3 (0258-0597-4609)
 
 1. SCOPE 
 As a part of the assembled Center for Research on Influenza Pathogenesis (CRIP), we have formed a unique animal influenza surveillance network structure that integrates research projects on influenza virus host responses, antigenicity, tropism and pathogenesis. We will dedicate resources and experienced personnel needed to rapidly detect influenza viruses by high throughput screening of collected samples and the phenotyping of select isolates. By contributing to an active and comprehensive animal influenza surveillance structure, we will be able to better understand the host range and ecology of influenza viruses, and the factors leading to the generation of pandemics. Additional research projects will further our knowledge of the determinants of influenza virus host tropism, pathogenicity, transmission, and impact on immunity needed to generate useful information to develop improved plans to mitigate the consequences of influenza virus outbreaks and pandemics. 
 
 2. TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS 
 Independently, and not as an agent of the Government, the Contractor shall furnish all necessary services, qualified professional, technical, and administrative personnel, material, equipment and facilities, not otherwise provided by the Government under the terms of this contract, as needed to perform the tasks set forth below. Specifically, the contractor shall undertake work in the areas of animal and/or human influenza surveillance research, pathogenesis and host responses as requested by NIAID. 
 
 Option 11A (0258-0544-4609)
 
 Determine if and when wild birds and free-ranging marine mammals in California are infected with novel Eurasian viruses (H5N2, H5N8) recently detected in the Pacific Northwest. 
 
 Determine if relevant viral strains existed in birds in Alaska prior to current isolations and if virus persists through the migratory cycle in the North American Pacific Flyway.
 
 Obtain isolates for genotypic and phenotypic studies at Mt Sinai and elsewhere to assess threat potential.  Samples detected in our proposed surveillance studies suspected positive for high path viruses will be shipped to SPRL for virus isolation, genotypic and phenotypic analysis in avian hosts, and to ISMMS for phenotypic characterization (antigenicity, replication, pathogenesis and transmission) in human cells, mice, guinea pigs and ferrets, in order to assess their potential risk.  These studies require select agent certified BSL3+ facilities, available at ISMMS. These studies will also be conducted in collaboration with other CRIP partners with BSL3+ capabilities.  We will start by characterizing the already isolated H5N8 and H5N2 viruses.
 
 Key sample sites for MIT include Interior Alaska and the Copper River Delta (Alaska). Secondary sampling sites will be engaged by MIT with collaborating institutions (Obihiro University, Novosibirsk University, other) in the East Asian Flyway if studies point towards further investigating links to Southeast Asia.  Free-ranging pinniped marine mammals (n~100 Northern Elephant Seal), will be captured and sampled from the Channel Islands (UC Davis) off the coast of southern California, CA.
 
 Option 17B (0258-0555-4609)
 
 1. SCOPE 
 As a part of the assembled Center for Research on Influenza Pathogenesis (CRIP), we will participate in the development of the Distributed Influenza Genome Sequencing (DIGS) project.
 
 2. SCIENTIFIC AND TECHNICAL ACTIVITIES
 
 1. Influenza Sequencing Core Related Work
 a. MIT shall begin research studies to develop and establish a sequencing methodology for single particle viral sequencing to be implemented in CEIRS DIGS. 
 b. MIT shall contribute expertise and consultation where possible to develop the overall project sequencing capability. 
 
 Option 18C (0258-0576-4609)
 
 Tasks
 1. Influenza Sequencing Core Related Work
 2. Influenza pandemic surveillance

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Phase 2 Scope of Work for Base Period
 
 The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.
 
 
 
 Phase 2:
 
 1. The attached work plan represents the aims and work to be carried out by the subcontractor to achieve the project goals.
 2. Subcontractor is required to provide a monthly invoice that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifth of the following month.  First report is due May 5, 2012.  Additional information should be included in the monthly report.  The monthly report format may change if CMS requests additional or different information on the monthly report.  An example monthly report template is attached.
 3. Consistent flow of data in from the Subcontractor s hospitals of at least 80%.
 4. Participation by Subcontractor program personnel at Contractor s national learning activities.
 5. An annual report at the end of 2012 and 2013.

column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTECHNOLOGY)
column76: The goal of the proposed research is to determine whether three different micro-engineered  organ-on-chip  microphysiological systems (Gut Chip, Bone Marrow Chip and Lung Chip) can serve as in vitro alternatives to in vivo screening of Medical Countermeasures (MCMs) for Acute Radiation Syndrome. In Phase 1 (24 months) of the Base Period (42 months), we will begin studies with a human Gut Chip that contains living human intestinal epithelial cells cultured within microfluidic devices that recapitulate the three- dimensional (3D) villus architecture and mechanically active microenvironment of the living intestine. Radiation sensitivity and MCM studies will be carried out using the gut chip in the presence or absence of a living microbiome. In addition, we will carry out experiments using a Bone Marrow Chip that is formed by engineering whole artificial bone in a living mouse, and then removing it and culturing it within a microfluidic device. Although we will begin with mouse marrow, we also will carry out studies to explore if we can replace the mouse marrow cells with cells from human cord blood to create a human Bone Marrow Chip.

Task 1: Project Communication and Management
  Project management: Participate in project management meetings with Child Trends and OPRE/ACF at least monthly with additional meetings as needed. Participate in additional coordination meetings with Child Trends, at least twice per month with additional meetings as needed. Provide monthly progress reports and invoices to Child Trends by 10th of each month for the preceding month. 
  Initial Discussion: Plan for and participate in the initial discussion with OPRE/ACF.  This will include in-person participation for the task lead.
 Task 2: Stakeholder Engagement Plan
  Identify stakeholders: Provide support identifying stakeholders and presenting ideas to OPRE/ACF.
  Review stakeholder engagement plan: Review sections of the stakeholder engagement plan.  All reviews and section drafts must be completed based on a mutually-agreed date that is at least three business days prior to the deliverable deadline.
  Participate in stakeholder engagement activities. Participate in the initial stakeholder engagement meeting.  Attend and lead break-out engagement activities as relevant to task 7 and to contractor s expertise.  Attend other meetings/trainings/presentations as requested.
 Task 3: Work Plan
  Review and provide input on project workplan. Ensure that contractor will be able to meet all timelines for deliverables.
  Discuss workplan changes early and often. Discuss adjustments to the workplan with the Child Trends team as soon as potential issues are identified.
 Task 4: Develop Dissemination Plan
  Review dissemination plan: Review the dissemination plan and provide feedback.  All reviews must be completed based on a mutually-agreed date that is at least three business days prior to the deliverable deadline.
 Task 5: Engage Experts
  Identify experts: Provide support identifying experts and presenting ideas to OPRE/ACF.
  Participate in expert activities. Participate in the initial expert meeting.  Attend and lead break-out engagement activities as relevant to task 7 and to contractor s expertise.  Attend other meetings/trainings/presentations as requested.
 Task 6: Understand Prevalence of IPV Among Fathers and RF populations
  Support the literature review: Help identify and summarize relevant sources for the literature review. Identify data sources that may provide additional sources of information.
  Review internal memo: Review and provide feedback on internal memo. All reviews must be completed based on a mutually-agreed date that is at least three business days prior to the deliverable deadline.
 Task 7: Understand Current Approaches to Addressing IPV in RF Grantees
  Serve as Task Lead. Dr. Megan Bair-Merritt will serve as task lead and ensure that all deliverables and activities are complete in a timely and accurate manner. She will ensure that all team members, experts, and stakeholders are actively engaged in this task in effort to create the highest quality product that upholds high standards of scientific rigor.
  Participate in data collection activities. Help develop data collection measures and protocols for all data collection. Conduct interviews and site visits with RF grantees and IPV program partners. Summarize qualitative data collection for these interviews and visits. Conduct program observations.  
  Provide input on pre-existing data, curricula, TA materials and other guidance.  Help identify and summarize relevant sources of information to understand current approaches to addressing IPV in RF grantees.
  Draft and review paper summary: Draft and review sections of this task summary.  All reviews and section drafts must be completed based on a mutually-agreed date that is at least three business days prior to the deliverable deadline.
 Task 9: Highlight Implications for RF Potential Approaches
  Provide input on substantive content for final report.
 Task 10: Ongoing dissemination activities

Attachment A
 Scope of Work for Harvard School of Public Health
 
 Background:  Harvard School of Public Health, will assist HRET in implementation of the AHRQ SUSP Ambulatory Surgery national project through providing expert input into overall strategy, assisting in monitoring key project metrics, providing necessary checklists, assisting in the development of the course design guide and improvement materials, and in training master trainers and change agents to support the project s implementation. HSOPH will also provide feedback to Westat regarding the SOPS for Ambulatory Surgery survey that will be developed. 
 
 Key Personnel:  The following individual/positions are designated as key personnel under this Agreement:
   Atul Guwande
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor plans to use and/or deliver the following pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights in its performance of this Agreement:
 
 - NONE
 
 Tasks:  
 
 1.  Participate in HRET-led efforts to identify and recruit TEP members and to plan and execute all TEP meetings required under the contract.
 2. Support the design, creation and enhancement of improvement resources required under the contract, including resources for participating facilities and for connector organizations working with these facilities.  Resources will include change packages (in electronic or print forms), Powerpoint presentations for use in meetings and on webinars, and video vignettes used to illustrate improvement concepts.  
 3. Provide feedback on the Ambulatory Surgery Center (ASC) Survey of Patient Safety Culture being developed by another HRET subcontractor and input on the ASC patient satisfaction measure being developed by CMS.
 4.  Supply checklists and other content relevant to the implementation guide and review and provide feedback on drafts of this document that HRET develops.  
 5. Support the implementation of ASC improvement activities by:
 a. Participating in the planning and execution of the stakeholder meeting.  
 b. Training the master trainers.  This will require helping HRET to conceptualize what training activities and materials are needed, serving as active participants in the planning and execution of these training activities, and providing ongoing coaching for trainees to fully equip them to work with ASCs.  
 c. Supporting the state-level implementation activities By attending kickoff meetings, leading webinars and conference calls with project participants, and mentoring other faculty performing these activities.
 6.  Assist in the selection of appropriate process and outcome measures for the project, provide feedback on resources that explain the measures and their validity to participants as well as how their data can be submitted, and assist HRET in reviewing the data and preparing reports for centers and the teams that are working with them.  
 7. Have at least one person on monthly planning calls with AHRQ and provide information HRET needs to complete monthly and other reports to AHRQ.

column76: Subtask 2.2 Monthly Project Status Meeting. The Subcontractor will participate, as needed in monthly project status meetings with Public Strategies and the Prime Client. Anticipate twelve (12) one-hour calls. Subtask 3.21 National Topic Centered Meeting. The Subcontractor will collaborate with MDRC to assist Public Strategies in the planning and delivery of one (1) National Topic Centered Meetings during the contract period. Public Strategies will handle logistics and be responsible for payment of any expert consultants identified to present during the meeting.  For this subtask, the Subcontractor will: Plan for Senior Advisor and EMPath Lead to attend a one (1)-day planning meeting in Washington, D.C.; Provide content materials and co-facilitate at the meeting; Staff the meeting with two (2) Executives and two to three (2-3) coaches anticipated to work with local sites; Budget all travel for staff for the planning meeting (anticipate 1 night) and National Topic-Centered Meeting (anticipate 2 nights) and per Diem at $201 for lodging and $69 M&IE. Timing of the National Topic-Centered Meeting is to be determined by Public Strategies and OFA COR. Subtask 3.22   Learning Community. The subcontractor will lead the TTA activities, in conjunction with Public Strategies, for six (6) of the ten (10) sites participating in the Learning Community. TTA activities will launch at the National Topic Centered Meeting and throughout the remainder of the contract year and will include providing relevant written resources/toolkits to sites, monthly calls with each site, periodic webinars, and two (2) site visits to each site. The EMPath coach is considered the Subject Matter Expert (SME) at each site for the TTA team. Subtask 3.24 Content-relevant Coaching. The subcontractor will assist Public Strategies in developing a virtual database of content-relevant TTA Coaches responsible for providing one-on-one support to TTA sites. Activities involved in the development of the virtual database include creating criteria for Coaches based on specific content areas determined by OFA and seeking guidance from experts related to identifying skilled and credentialed professionals with content and technical knowledge. Personnel: EMPath will designate a Senior Advisor, an EMPath Lead, and a list of 2-3 coaches to work as Subject Matter Experts with local sites. Any changes to these personnel must be submitted to Public Strategies and approved by Public Strategies and the Prime Client.

These sera will be tested against target cells (A549) infected with wild type H7N9 strain, which is BSL3+ (alternatively could test attenuated H7N9 strains such as A/Shanghai/2/2103 generated for vaccine production, which is BSL2_).  As a positive control in the CDL and ADCC assays, target cells infected with either seasonal or 2009 pandemic H1N1 strain or a seasonal H3N2 strain will be used depending on when the serum samples were collected.
