column76:
Statement of Work for PEN grant Project 1
 Work at MIT involve the design and synthesis of polymer, formulation of nanoparticles, generation of libraries of nanoparticles with cyclin A2 followed by screening tests on the libraries. The recently developed biodegrabale polymer nanoparticles by MIT group will be synthesized and optimized for transfection of cardiac cells using combinatorial end-modfication of poly (b-amino ester)s. Various parameters important for the gene delivery like, size, cytotoxicity, and uptake will be studied. Each cationic nanoparticle wtih a polymer:DNA ratio of 20:1 will be made and combined with pEGFP-N1 plasmid DNA binding followed with transfection study using cultured rat and human cardiac cells. Short listed three nanoparticle formulations with highest GFP luminescence in the tested cell types will be used for further anlaysis for nanoparticle size, DNA binding, DNA uptake and cytotoxicity to determine the best particle for the cardiac gene delivery applications. These in vitro transfection studies will be repeated in the presence and absence of Gelfoam hydrogel carrier for pericardial delivery and the effects will be examined by variation of transfection times.The best two nanoparticle formulation from the above studies will be scaled up and shipped to MSSM for further testing with 2-D and 3-D in vitro cyclin A2 gene delivery assays. These studies will examine the effects of cyclin A2 nanoparticles on cardiomyocyte proliferation and regional contractile function. In vivo biodistrubtion and toxicity in Balb c mice will be studied with these nanoparticles will be studied at MIT. Further these nanoparticles will be tested in vivo in porcine models.
 On the whole, the polymer synthesis, nanoparticle formulation, and screening tests will be performed at MIT, where all necessary expertise and equipment for nanoparticle synthesis and DNA transfection is available. Cells will be isolated and differentiated at MSSM, and shipped to MIT for testing if possible. In vivo studies will be carried out at both MIT and MSSM.
 Statement of Work for PEN Project 3
 Work at MIT will involve design and synthesis of different lipid-hybrid nanoparticles with PLGA core and PEG-phospholipid shell. Different compositions of statin, Iron oxide (IO), gold (Au) nanocrystals, detachable-PEGylated-phospholipids, and a macrophage targeting ligand, mannose containing PEG-phosholipids will be used to for the generation of library of theranostic nanoparticles. Initially macrophage targeted lipid-hybrid nanoparticles with smaller sizes and higher statin loading in the PLGA core will be developed and characterized for size, surface charge, loading, encapsulation efficiency. This formulation to will be further optimized for conditions to make nanoparticles with encapsulated IO and Au nanocrystals along with statin in the PLGA core. These nanoparticles stability, statin release, IO release and Au release will be studied in vitro. Futher surface switching by measuring the PEG detachability in the presence of MMP2 from atherosclerotic plaques and targeting efficacy of the resultant nanoparticles with exposed mannose groups on the surface will be studied in vitro. These theranostic
 nanoparticles will be screened for slow drug release, higher statin and imaging agent loading
 and PEG detachability. The short listed candidates will be used for cellular uptake
 measurements using various imaging or microscopy techniques. Also these nanoparticles will
 be studied for in vitro cytotoxicity measurements to measure the therapeutic efficacy. Further
 short listed candidates from the in vitro studies will be scaled up used to study for in vivo
 efficacy, imaging experiments which will be conducted at MIT or the co-PI lab in New York.
 Further histological analysis will be carried to assess the effects of the therapy using these
 theranostic nanoparticles.
 PEN Nanotech Core Statement of Work
 The Nanotechnology Core (Nano Core) objectives are: (i) to provide consultation to
 investigators of projects 1   3 on methodology for the formulation and optimization of drugloaded
 multifunctional polymeric and lipid-polymer hybrid nanoparticles; and (ii) to provide
 investigators of projects 1 and 3 with the services to scale up the synthesis of their lead
 nanoparticles formulations in a sterile fashion suitable for efficacy studies in rabbits and pigs.
 Nano Core will provide consultation services including (a) technical advising, (b) nanoparticle
 formulation process development related to each project, followed by technology transfer to
 members of the PEN consortium. Additionally, the members of the project 1   3 research team
 may spend time develop skill set necessary after technology transfer in order to formulate
 nanoparticles in a reproducible and a robust manner. The process development for scale up
 manufacturing of nanoparticles will be done by the Nanocore in support of large animal studies
 proposed in project 1 and 3. An appropriate batch size for production of the drug-encapsulated
 targeted nanoparticles will be determined based on the scope of efficacy studies, toxicological
 studies, and stability requirements for their respective application. Suitable equipment and
 process parameters for nanoparticle formation, collection, drying and sterilization will be
 identified based on particle size, drug load, drug release kinetics, residual solvent levels and the
 ability to resuspend the dried nanoparticles. Experimental work will be performed to determine
 critical process parameters, equipment size, material requirements and scaling factors. Key
 process parameters dictating scalability include the starting concentrations of polymer and drug,
 the ratio of organic to aqueous phase and the manner in which the organic and aqueous phases
 are brought into contact. We will evaluate the effect of these parameters with the objective of
 maximizing particle yield and encapsulation efficiency while achieving the same mean particle
 diameter that was initially found to be optimal for each project as part of their small animal
 efficacy studies. Each large-scale batch will be subject to the same battery of biopharmaceutical
 tests as the small-scale formulations prior to testing of nanoparticles in large animals. We will
 also determine alternative approaches to sterilization with respect to their effects on
 nanoparticle quality, degree of sterility assurance and ease of validation.

column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

Products may include technical tools and supporting documentation and materials for use internal or external to EPA.

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Phase 2 Scope of Work for Base Period
 
 The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.
 
 
 
 Phase 2:
 
 1. The attached work plan represents the aims and work to be carried out by the subcontractor to achieve the project goals.
 2. Subcontractor is required to provide a monthly invoice that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifth of the following month.  First report is due May 5, 2012.  Additional information should be included in the monthly report.  The monthly report format may change if CMS requests additional or different information on the monthly report.  An example monthly report template is attached.
 3. Consistent flow of data in from the Subcontractor s hospitals of at least 80%.
 4. Participation by Subcontractor program personnel at Contractor s national learning activities.
 5. An annual report at the end of 2012 and 2013.

column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES (EXCEPT BIOTECHNOLOGY)
column76: The goal of the proposed research is to determine whether three different micro-engineered  organ-on-chip  microphysiological systems (Gut Chip, Bone Marrow Chip and Lung Chip) can serve as in vitro alternatives to in vivo screening of Medical Countermeasures (MCMs) for Acute Radiation Syndrome. In Phase 1 (24 months) of the Base Period (42 months), we will begin studies with a human Gut Chip that contains living human intestinal epithelial cells cultured within microfluidic devices that recapitulate the three- dimensional (3D) villus architecture and mechanically active microenvironment of the living intestine. Radiation sensitivity and MCM studies will be carried out using the gut chip in the presence or absence of a living microbiome. In addition, we will carry out experiments using a Bone Marrow Chip that is formed by engineering whole artificial bone in a living mouse, and then removing it and culturing it within a microfluidic device. Although we will begin with mouse marrow, we also will carry out studies to explore if we can replace the mouse marrow cells with cells from human cord blood to create a human Bone Marrow Chip.

column54: BETH ISRAEL DEACONESS MEDICAL CENTER, INC
column76: The Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center will collaborate with the Massachusetts General Hospital as part of this contract. Specifically, Dr. Gerszten will perform a targeted metabolomics analysis of ~100 organic acids and related molecules on 2000 de-identified human plasma samples that are chosen by the NHLBI. His platform will process raw LC-MS data to generate lists of metabolites and their signal intensities in each sample. The platform will conduct quality control analyses using internal standard data and pooled sample reference data collected during the analyses. Final datasets will be shared in ascii text or MS Excel format. Dr. Gerszten will assist with assessment of data quality and interpretation of the results.

column76:
The Broad Institute has established a mass spectrometry-based Metabolite Profiling Platform to
 enable comprehensive analyses of endogenous metabolites in biological specimens. Dr. Clary Clish serves as a PI and the Director of this platform. In this proposal, Broad Metabolite Profiling Platform will be used to measure metabolic profiles in 2000 de-identified plasma samples.
 Dr. Clish will be responsible for all metabolite profiling activities conducted at the Broad
 Institute. 2000 plasma samples will be analyzed in total. Each sample will be aliquoted into two
 sub-samples for LC-MS analyses using two methods, a lipid profiling method and a polar metabolite profiling method operated in the positive ionization mode. The platform will process raw LC-MS data to generate lists of metabolites and their signal intensities in each sample. The platform will conduct quality control analyses using internal standard data and pooled sample reference data collected during the analyses. Final datasets will be shared in ascii text or MS Excel format. Dr. Clish will assist with assessment of data quality and interpretation of the results.

 and analysis.

column76:
Option Year Scope of Work:
 Tasks:
 1. Subcontractor agrees to work with and track progress of participating acute, critical access (CAH) and children s hospitals on implementing improvement interventions, submitting data, and analyzing data to guide improvement in all topics. Specifically, subcontractor will be required to work with participating hospitals on the topics below. Hospitals can be exempt from working on CLABSI, OB Adverse Events, SSI and/or VAE only if they do not provide these inpatient services.
 a. Adverse drug events (ADE), including at a minimum, opioid safety, anticoagulation safety, and glycemic management
 b. Catheter-associated urinary tract infections (CAUTI), in all hospital settings, including the placement of catheters in the ER.
 c. Central line-associated blood stream infections (CLASBI), in all hospital settings, not just Intensive Care Units (ICUs)
 d. Injuries from falls and immobility
 e. Obstetrical adverse events, including Early Elective Deliveries (EED) reduction.  Expand obstetrical adverse events to include, at minimum, obstetrical hemorrhage, and preeclampsia treatment and management to prevent morbidity and mortality.
 f. Pressure Ulcers
 g. Surgical Site Infections, to include measurement and improvement of SSI for multiple classes of surgeries
 h. Venous thromboembolism (VTE), including, at a minimum, all surgical settings
 i. Ventilator-Associated Events (VAE), to include Infection-related Ventilator-Association Complication (IVAC) and Ventilator-Associated Pneumonia (VAP)
 j. Readmissions
 2. Continue to carry out the activities as defined in subcontractor option year work plan.  The contractor will discuss progress on the activities of the option year work plan and provide opportunity to subcontractor to make adjustments as needed at least monthly. 
 3. Continue to have the subcontractor program personnel participate at national program activities promoted by the AHA/HRET HEN including but not limited to: AHA/HRET HEN educational offerings, CMS/National Content Developer events, etc. 
 4. Continue to have the subcontractor program personnel participate at subcontractor meetings held by the Contractor.
 5. Continue to actively promote and highly encourage participation in the national educational offerings including but not limited AHA/HRET HEN educational offerings, CMS/National Content Developer events, etc. to all participating hospitals.
 6. Continue to provide technical assistance and support to participating hospitals to ensure that methods proposed to reduce the ten core harm events are implemented.  Such technical assistance may include establishing learning collaborative, developing data sharing networks and developing mechanisms to support peer to peer training among hospitals.
 7. Continue to work collaboratively with other subcontractors to foster a peer-to-peer learning and sharing environment to advance the overall project goals.
 8. Continue to coordinate with other Partnership for Patients (PFP) participants and stakeholders including the QIO community and the Community Based Care Transitions Program where applicable to collect and share data and other elements necessary to implement, operate, and evaluate the PFP, and to achieve the shared aims of the project while working to eliminate duplication.
 9. Continue to work with all acute/CAH/children s hospitals to align measurement, ensure minimally 80 percent of acute/CAH/children s hospitals are submitting at least eight data points on all applicable topics, and monitor progress towards the overall project goal of 40% reduction of harm and 20% reduction of readmission by December 8, 2014.

column76:
IHI will assist and collaborate with Westat as a member of the project team in its contract with AHRQ and the Office of the National Coordinator (ONC) to plan, implement, maintain, and evaluate the KSN for the Health Information Technology Research Center (HITRC.)  Under Tasks 2 and 3 the team will be developing the requirements of the KSN and building Communities of Practice (CoPs) for the HITRC and specifically for the Regional Extension Centers.   The team will leverage IHI s experiences and tools/materials from design, training, and support of both its learning networks and its large communities of practices supporting hospitals.Task 2   Planning and Design of KSN
 IHI s role:  
   Assist Westat in selecting the initial three CoP domains (unless already determined by AHRQ/ONC)
   Assist Westat in designing the  model  and general operating procedures for the CoPs
   Based on IHI s pre-existing material, contribute prototype training materials that can be used to support the facilitation of the CoPs (e.g., CoP facilitation, role of the  champion,  etc.)   these materials would be adapted to facilitate the REC demonstrations
   Assist in conducting rapid design meetings in support of KSN design and provide feedback on the final KSN plans 
   Support Westat in the design and testing of methods to engage participants in CoPs to create vibrant learning communities (including development of surveys and meeting discussion guides as appropriate)
   Assist Westat in determining REC capabilities/needs, as well as the level of REC staff motivation for cross-REC learning and sharing
   Assist Westat in the development of the REC demonstration and supporting materials
 
 
 
 
 
 
 General Performance Expectations:  
 
 Prepare and provide technical, management, price, and schedule data and materials, and otherwise participate in and support the prime contract proposal activities as assigned. 
 
 Prepare and deliver a timely, responsive, and reasonable proposal in response to the Prime Contractor s reasonable requirements and the RFP. The Subcontractor s proposal shall be compliant with Client flowdown requirements.
 
 Provide an agreed upon number of competent personnel at the Prime Contractor s facility or at the Subcontractor s facility to assist in the effective and timely integration of data and material into the prime contract proposal.
 
 Participate in periodic proposal technical and management reviews and presentations as well as in the marketing and public relations aspects of the Program as requested by the Prime Contractor.
 
 Assist the Prime Contractor as requested in the development of a definitive subcontract statement of work for the proposed subcontract responsibilities and scope of work set forth in Attachment 1.
 
 
 Task 3: Implementation
 IHI s Role:  
   In Year 1, have one IHI representative attend select regional REC meetings (up to four), as directed by Westat
 o At select REC meetings (up to four), support the team in CoP pre-recruiting activities by assessing domain interest and determining ways to reduce the perceived burden of CoP participation 
 o At select REC meetings (up to four), demonstrate the KSN and CoP model(s)Assist in the development of the  spread  plan to expand the CoPs 
   Assist in developing the feedback system to continually improve the functioning and value of the CoPs for the participants
   Take the lead on the implementation of new CoPs and manage them over the course of the contract
 o Up to 8 new CoPs in Year 2, based on discussions between Westat and IHI
 o Up to 12 new CoPs in Year 3, based on discussions between Westat and IHI
 o Up to 5 new CoPs in Year 4, based on discussions between Westat and IHI
 o As part of this work, identify topics of interest, support development of tools within the KSN, identify champions, complete content integration (as needed), facilitate monthly CoP conference calls, provide access to expert resources and a bridge to technical assistance

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.

 1. TBD

 Key Personnel

 TASKS:
 1. Support the design, creation and enhancement of improvement resources required under the contract, including resources for participating facilities and for connector organizations working with these facilities. Resources will include change packages (in electronic print forms), PowerPoint presentations for use in meetings and on webinars and video vignettes used to illustrate improvement concepts.

This will require helping HRET to conceptualize what training activities and materials are needed, serving as active participants, in the planning and execution of these training activities and providing ongoing coaching for trainees to fully equip them to work with ASCs.
 c. Supporting national implementation activities by attending kickoff meetings, leading webinars, learning groups and conference calls with project participants, and mentoring other faculty performing these activities.
 4. Participate in the planning and execution of 5-10 site visits to participating ASCs for the purpose of developing best practices and lessons learned for the project.
 a. Participate in monthly Site Visit / Measurement Committee calls
 5. Contribute to the development of manuscripts focusing on project learnings and participate on the manuscript Committee.
 6. Assist in the selection of appropriate process and outcome measures for the project, provide feedback on resources that explain the measures and their validity to participants as well as how their data can be submitted, and assist HRET in reviewing the data and preparing reports for centers and the teams that are working with them.
 7. Have at least one person on monthly planning calls with AHRQ and provide information HRET needs to complete monthly and other reports to AHRQ.
 DELIVERABLES:

Dr. Marfeo, Co-investigator, will participate on the NIH Contract titled Post Development Testing of the 
 Functional Assessment Battery. Dr. Marfeo is an Assistant Professor at Tufts University and Director of the 
 Health and Productive Aging Lab. Dr. Marfeo's research interests include measurement development, 
 work disability and healthy aging across the adult lifespan. Specifically, Dr. Marfeo's primary research goals  are directed towards understanding the interactions between environmental demands, adaptations, and 
 aging as it affects a person's health related quality of life including participating in the workforce. Since  2009, Dr. Marfeo has been a Co-Investigator on the SSA-NIH-BU projects aimed at developing a measure  using contemporary psychometric methods (item response theory and computer adaptive testing) in order 
 to capture a person s ability to work. Dr. Marfeo also received funding as a PI on a NIH R24 pilot project 
 that used the Round 1 2011 National Health and Aging Trends Study (NHATS) to examine contextual 
 factors and community participation among older adults. Dr. Marfeo will collaborate with teams at SSA, 
 NIH and Boston University to develop project protocols, provide input on measurement development, 
 assist with content expertise (occupational therapy, work disability assessment, measurement 
 development) in the development of materials, contribute to manuscripts, and disseminate project 
 findings. Her effort on the project will be 20% FTE.

column43: NATIONAL IMPLEMENTATION OF COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CATHETER-ASSOCIATED URINARY TRACT INFECTION (CAUTI)
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE SOCIAL SCIENCES AND HUMANITIES
column76:
Scope of Work 
 
 In August 2011, AHRQ sought to deploy and implement a program for the support and expansion of the adoption and use of a CUSP that can be applied to reduce CAUTI in hospitals in all States, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico through State-based or regional consortia/collaborative in a phased approach.  This work builds upon and expands the current activities to demonstrate the effectiveness of CUSP for CAUTI in twelve States.  This follow-on effort utilizes the resources and materials for CUSP for CAUTI that have been developed as part of earlier contract work for this expansion of the national implementation effort.  
 
 The total funding for Subcontractor s effort is $20,000 U.S. Dollars in the Base Year and $50,000 in the Option Year. Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the following tasks and deliverables in excess of this amount.  
 
 TASKS:
 
 1. Ensure the recruitment and continued active participation of at least 10 hospitals in the project.
 2. Obtain and maintain general knowledge of the project (goals, expectations, interventions, timelines, schedules, etc.) and serve as a liaison between the national project team and hospital units.
 3. Work with unit teams to assist with culture improvements and overcoming project barriers.
 4. Provide individual coaching with identified high outliers.
 5. Regularly participate in scheduled calls with the national project team and encourage participating hospitals to do the same.
 6. Work with extended faculty to develop specific state curriculum needs.
 7. Commit to the goal of reducing mean CAUTI rates in participating clinical units by 25 percent, and improving safety culture as evidenced by improved teamwork and communication by employing CUSP methodology.  
 
 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Provide a part-time project coordinator to function as the state lead.
 2. Monitor and coordinate with participating hospitals to assure their submission of:
 a. Monthly infection rate data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 b. AHRQ Safety Culture surveys at the beginning and end of the project
 c. Quarterly team check up tool data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 3. Submit the State Lead Monthly Status Report (Attachment E).
 4. Facilitate monthly coaching calls and establish agendas for them.
 5. Coordinate three face-to-face learning sessions (at the start of the project, at mid-collaborative, and at the end of the collaborative).
 6. Coordinate site visits to units as needed.

 Project Dates: October 1, 2012- August 31, 2013
 The Broad Institute, in support of the above study, will:
   Receive approximately 1575 DNA samples, quantify DNA using PicoGreen or other appropriate methods.
   Perform fingerprint genotyping and gender checks on approximately 1575 samples.

   Perform quality control on assay results from each experiment.
   Deliver called genotypes to the collaborators.

column76: The team at Subcontractor #1 shall continue to provide a pool of potential study participants who are receiving homogenous irradiation to their teeth as part of therapeutic total body irradiation (TBI). This population, who have received prescribed homogeneous (and known) doses at a level appropriate to model exposures from nuclear events, are uniquely qualified to provide accurate models of the situation for which the technology is aimed: after-the-fact determination of exposure to radiation of levels that could lead to the acute radiation syndrome. The capabilities of the instruments developed by the Prime Contractor and engineering subcontractors will be evaluated using study participants recruited from patients of Subcontractor #1 who are receiving or have received radiation doses in the pertinent dose range, through measurements made at the site of Subcontractor #1 or at the site of the Prime Contractor, by referral from Subcontractor #1 for measurements in patients who previously completed therapy, if this is more convenient for the patient.   Using these groups of human subjects, data will be obtained that will aid in the development of appropriate calibration curves, using in vivo EPR directly in the populations of interest, using the devices specifically designed for such use.  The measurements will be made by operators who are part of the irradiating facility who have received training and ongoing support by the Prime Contractor.

column43: IGF::CL::IGF CLOSELY ASSOCIATED - ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING SUPPORT FOR CLEAN WATER REGULATIONS
column76:
Subcontractor will support the collection of the ecological risk parameter data necessary to translate modeled selenium water and sediment concentrations into quantified ecological risk endpoints for each of the 297 immediate receiving waters where ERG has modeled steady-state water and sediment concentrations. This support may include, but is not limited to, participation in discussions with ERG staff (e.g., emails and/or conference calls); review of ERG-developed materials (e.g., spreadsheet data compilations); and discussions with subject matter experts on modeling of ecological risk associated with bioaccumulative metals. The contractor will provide this support for the following ERG efforts:
  
 Review of published studies to collect site-specific selenium Kd factors and supporting documentation regarding their development (e.g., field sampling methods and timeframe) and the receiving water characteristics (e.g., flow rate, lake depth).
  
 Evaluation of whether sufficient site-specific data are available (e.g., TSS monitoring data) to support development of additional site-specific selenium Kd factors.
  
 Development of Kd factor distributions for each immediate receiving water, based on aggregation of selected field study Kd factors that are intended to closely represent the immediate receiving water.
  
 Review of published studies to collect species-specific selenium trophic transfer factors (TTFs) for various species of invertebrates, fish, and birds.
  
 Development of TTF distributions for each trophic level that are intended to closely represent the likely food web present within each immediate receiving water. This effort will emphasize TTFs for those species that are known to be an endpoint of interest or that are known to be prey for a predator endpoint of interest (e.g., bird species for which we have dietary dose-response data on egg hatchability).
  
 Review and incorporation of applicable dietary dose-response data for species endpoints of interest.
   Evaluation and incorporation of methods to validate and calibrate modeled tissue concentrations at each trophic level, with the goal of avoiding propagation of outlier data through the food web.

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Phase 2 Scope of Work for Base Period
 
 The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.
 
 
 
 Phase 2:
 
 1. The attached work plan represents the aims and work to be carried out by the subcontractor to achieve the project goals.
 2. Subcontractor is required to provide a monthly invoice that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifth of the following month.  First report is due May 5, 2012.  Additional information should be included in the monthly report.  The monthly report format may change if CMS requests additional or different information on the monthly report.  An example monthly report template is attached.
 3. Consistent flow of data in from the Subcontractor s hospitals of at least 80%.
 4. Participation by Subcontractor program personnel at Contractor s national learning activities.
 5. An annual report at the end of 2012 and 2013.

1. As Westat s Subcontractor, Earley & Associates shall develop the KSN taxonomy to tag and compile a unified knowledge base for the HITRC and meta data searches for sharing documentation and reference materials on interest to CoPs.
 
 2. The subcontractor will return to Westat s project manager a signed Confidentiality and Non-disclosure Agreement for every person working on the KSN. Westat will forward the forms to Earley & Associates as soon as the client provides them to Westat (date TBD).  Subcontractor will return the completed forms within five business days of receipt.
 
 
 3. Subcontractor will work closely with Westat to describe the approach and methodology to be used, as well as to establish the Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) clearly defining the work to be done by Earley & Associates for deliverables 2.6, 2.8, 4.2.5, 4.2.6, and 5.3.1. This input is essential to ensure the accuracy and effectiveness of the comprehensive work plan and guarantee that AHRQ contract deliverables are on time and within budget.
 
 4. Subcontractor shall provide the Westat Project Manager or her designee by noon of the fifth day of each month a written progress report on the activities accomplished during the prior month, how these accomplishments compare with planned milestones and a discussion of unmet milestones including their impact on the deliverables schedule and actions planned to alleviate the problem. There should be (at a minimum) summaries for each subtask in Attachment 2. Although official monthly invoices are not due until the 15th day of the month, the progress report should include sufficient budget information to allow Westat to evaluate costs and report this information to AHRQ/ONC in the KSN monthly progress report. If the fifth day falls on a weekend, the report should be delivered on the Friday prior.
 
 
 5. Subcontractor shall provide to Westat s Project Manager or her designee the deliverables specified in Attachment 2 at least five business days prior to the date from the Master Schedule.  The Master Schedule is attached; this schedule is expected to change based on the requirements of the project and the study sponsor (AHRQ).  Such dates will allow for Westat s review of the deliverable prior to official delivery to AHRQ.
 
 6. Subcontractor will maintain a log of standard operating procedures for taxonomy modification to be incorporated in project wide SOPs (Westat s delivery date is 6 weeks prior to end of Westat s contract with AHRQ, so Earley & Associated would deliver no later than 7 weeks prior to contract end). 
 
 
 7. On an as-needed basis, the subcontractor shall participate in scheduled conference calls with Westat and AHRQ to report on the taxonomy s progress and any issues that arise. 
 
 8. On an as-needed basis, travel to Rockville, MD for in person meetings with Westat.
 
 
 9. Prepare and provide technical, management, price, and schedule data and materials, and otherwise participate in and support the prime contract proposal activities as assigned. 
 
 10. Prepare and deliver a timely, responsive, and reasonable proposal in response to the Prime Contractor s reasonable requirements and the RFP. The Subcontractor s proposal shall be compliant with Client flowdown requirements.
 
 11. Provide an agreed upon number of competent personnel at the Prime Contractor s facility or at the Subcontractor s facility to assist in the effective and timely integration of data and material into the prime contract proposal.
 
 12. Participate in periodic proposal technical and management reviews and presentations as well as in the marketing and public relations aspects of the Program as requested by the Prime Contractor.
 
 13. Assist the Prime Contractor as requested in the development of a definitive subcontract statement of work for the proposed subcontract responsibilities and scope of work set forth in Attachment A attached hereto.

column76: The goal of the proposed research is to determine whether three different micro-engineered  organ-on-chip  microphysiological systems (Gut Chip, Bone Marrow Chip and Lung Chip) can serve as in vitro alternatives to in vivo screening of Medical Countermeasures (MCMs) for Acute Radiation Syndrome. In Phase 1 (24 months) of the Base Period (42 months), we will begin studies with a human Gut Chip that contains living human intestinal epithelial cells cultured within microfluidic devices that recapitulate the three- dimensional (3D) villus architecture and mechanically active microenvironment of the living intestine. Radiation sensitivity and MCM studies will be carried out using the gut chip in the presence or absence of a living microbiome. In addition, we will carry out experiments using a Bone Marrow Chip that is formed by engineering whole artificial bone in a living mouse, and then removing it and culturing it within a microfluidic device. Although we will begin with mouse marrow, we also will carry out studies to explore if we can replace the mouse marrow cells with cells from human cord blood to create a human Bone Marrow Chip.

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012.

Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).

 1. TBD

 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process. column76: Conduct CDL and ADCC assays of human sera from the following experimental human viccine studies:  10 serasamples from H7N7 vaccine trial (pre- and postvaccination); 10 sera samples from H5N1 vaccine trial (pre- and post-vaccination); 5 sera samples from H7N7 LAIV/IV study (pre- and post vaccination); human mAbs to H7 (positive controls); and 3 sets of pre- and post-seasonal viccine sera and include seasonal H1 virus infected target cells in the CDL and ADCC assays.  These sera will be tested against target cells (A549) infected with wild type H7N9 strain, which is BSL3+ (alternatively could test attenuated H7N9 strains such as A/Shanghai/2/2103 generated for vaccine production, which is BSL2_).  As a positive control in the CDL and ADCC assays, target cells infected with either seasonal or 2009 pandemic H1N1 strain or a seasonal H3N2 strain will be used depending on when the serum samples were collected.

column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF  EXPANDING THE COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CENTRAL LINE-ASSOCIATED BLOOD STREAM INFECTIONS (CLABSI) AND  (CAUTI) IN INTENSIVE CARE UNITS WITH PERSISTENTLY ELEVATED INFECTION RATES
column76:
Attachment A
 Scope of Work for Cohort 4 
 
 Background: Healthcare-associated infections, or HAIs, are a highly significant cause of illness and death for patients in the U.S. health care system. At any given time, HAIs affect one out of every 25 hospital inpatients. More than a million of these infections occur across our health care system every year, leading to significant patient harm and the annual loss of tens of thousands of lives, and costing billions of dollars each year. Some of the most prevalent HAIs include: surgical site infections (SSIs), Catheter-Associated Urinary Tract Infections (CAUTI), Central-Line Associated Blood Stream Infections (CLABSI), and ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP). It is estimated that CAUTIs affect approximately 250,000 hospital patients per year, and approximately 40,000 CLABSI cases occur annually with a mortality rate from 12 to 25 percent.
 
 Key Personnel:  The following individual/positions are designated as key personnel under this Agreement:
 [____] 
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor plans to use and/or deliver the following pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights in its performance of this Agreement:
 
 Each participating State Lead (SL) will work to coordinate the program in their state, understand program onboarding and educational materials in order to coach units appropriately, and is responsible for performing the following tasks. 
 
 Tasks:
 1. Attend in-person kick-off meeting in Chicago on June 7, 2018 (travel for up to two (2) individuals to be covered by HRET) prior to the start of the project 
 a. If unable to attend in-person kick-off meeting, SL must watch all onboarding webinars and provide documentation of viewership
 b. Recommend identifying and recruiting at least one state-level clinical mentor to provide clinical support for units throughout the program. If clinical mentor is identified, (s)he must watch all onboarding webinars and provide documentation of viewership
 2. Develop and submit State Implementation Plan (template to be provided by HRET) after the kick-off meeting to their HRET Quality Improvement Coach. The plan should evaluate the current CLABSI and CAUTI prevention strategies and how the SL and clinical mentor can complement existing strategies and address gaps that may exist, as well as plans for sustaining improvement. HRET will provide a template for SLs to use and due date at the Kick-off.
 3. Recruit and register eligible units to participate in Cohort 4 by July 15, 2018. 
 a. Eligible units are those that meet the established criteria for persistently elevated infection rates (PEIR) as confirmed by NHSN TAP reports
 4. 90% of eligible participating units must submit ICU Assessment (template to be provided by HRET) into CDS within the submission timeframe 
 5. 90% of eligible participating units must submit ICU Action Plan (template to be provided by HRET) into CDS within four (4) weeks after receiving ICU Assessment results 
 6. SL and clinical mentor to review and become familiar with programmatic and educational materials prior to unit participation in project to support their coaching efforts
 7. Ensure units meet program education and data requirements and intervene as soon as challenges become apparent (within 30 days). These requirements include:
 a. Education requirements:
 i. participation in all onboarding webinars hosted by HRET
 ii. accessing HRET e-learning modules and other project toolkit materials based on needs identified in action plan
 iii. attending monthly virtual learning group (VLG) webinars hosted by HRET 
 b. Data requirements: 
 i. conferring rights to HRET s NHSN group (instructions for conferring rights will be provided at the kick-off meeting)
 ii. If NHSN rights are not conferred to HRET for data submission, SL must submit all required data on a monthly basis to HRET (details for data metrics will be provide at kick-off meeting)
 8. Have, at a minimum, monthly check-ins with all PEIR units, including those making good progress. Monthly check-ins should include a review of the unit s:
 a. Successes and challenges
 b. Rates and trends of CLABSI and/or CAUTI rates and device utilization
 c. Progress in unit s action plan 
 9. Have monthly check-ins with HRET Quality Improvement Coach
 10. Attend monthly coaching calls and Virtual Learning group (VLG) webinars hosted by HRET
 a. Identify unit presenters as needed for VLGs
 11. Submit quarterly progress reports (template to be provided by HRET), which will include tracking progress to the ICUs  action plans, through platform provided by HRET 
 12. Submit at least one case study (template to be provided by HRET) on implementation successes and/or challenges from participating units
 13. Coordinate and attend unit site visits (all costs to be covered by SL) to 30% of eligible participating units (site visits may be shared between SL and clinical mentor).
 a. At least one site visit to include National Project Team (NPT) subject matter experts (SME) (travel expenses for NPT SMEs to be covered by HRET)
 b. Submit site visit report for each site visit into CDS (template to be provided by HRET)
 i. Site visit report to be submitted within 30 days of site visit
 14. OPTIONAL: Hold at least one (1) in-person state-level meeting (all costs to be covered by SL)
 15. OPTIONAL: Attend cohort close-out meeting if scheduled by HRET (travel for up to two (2) individuals to be covered by HRET)
  
 ATTACHMENT B

column43: TAS::75 0846::TAS NCS THE NATIONAL CHILDREN'S STUDY VANGUARD CENTER

column67: Contracts and Grants,Educational Institution,Research and Development,U.S. State Government
column76:
As part of the National Children s Study Vanguard Center, we will analyze 570 samples for Hg, Pb, Cd, As concentration and Hg, Pb, and As speciation analysis of selected samples by ICP-MS and GC-ICP-MS. We consider this project the first priority for UMB researchers Darrah and Campbell during the outlined study period (Mar 4, 2011 to March 3, 2013: Yr1: 03/04/11-03/03/12; Yr 2: 03/04/12-03/03/13). Both Co-PI Dr. T. Darrah and M.E. Campbell, M.S. express willingness to actively participate in NCS publications, reports, and intellectual property as coordinated by Drs. Landrigan and Miller. These researchers, with the permission of Drs. Landrigan and Miller will publish relevant metals and speciation data. 
 
 I. Background 
 Existing collaborations between PI Miller (URMC) and Co-PI Darrah (UMB) have focused on developing novel experimental and analytical techniques to evaluate the abundance and biokinetics of metal particles to the developing fetus. In our Metallomics Laboratory at UMass Boston, we (Co-PI Darrah and Ms. M.E. Campbell, M.S.) have successfully analyzed placental perfusate and tissue samples as part of previous NIH funded projects (NIH NICHHD R03 HD059027). Our contributions to the NCS Project 18 study, which directly support the current proposal, include the development of analytical methods to measure concentrations and species of Pb, As, Hg, Cd, in placental tissues by ICP-MS and GC-ICP-MS.
 
 II.  Technical Requirements
 The UMB subcontractor is responsible for determining the concentrations of toxic metals Pb, Hg, Cd, and As in placental tissue by a combination of ICP-MS and Hg analyzer. The use of ICP-MS enables simultaneous determination of multiple trace elements in each placental tissue sample at no additional cost, providing full screening for potentially toxic trace metals at the cost of only four metals. Speciation of Hg, As, and Pb will be evaluated by GC-ICP-MS in a subset of samples that exhibit total concentrations of each metal above pre-determined  toxic threshold  concentrations. In addition, we will evaluate the stability of tissue and metal concentrations at various times between birth and sample collection, and validate placental tissue sample collections methods for the Main NCS study and other academic placental projects. 
 
 UMB will be responsible for developing a written and video standard operating procedure (SOP) for sample storage, preparation, instrument calibration, analysis, and data processing. After the completion of sample analyses, a statistical evaluation of data will be completed by UMB PI Darrah and data will be reported to the UR data Management Core (18.7). Data will be analyzed to determine if there are detectable and statistically significant differences in metal contamination according to time elapsed between birth and collection and in different geographic areas included in the pilot study.
 
 III.  Specific Activities
 The Project 18-Placental Tissue proposal is designed to evaluate the influence of the previously stated variables (sample collection timing) on data quality and to generate preliminary data to demonstrate study feasibility in a time period of approximately 3 months following sample collection initiation. As a result, all analyses, SOP publications, statistical treatment of data, and database development will occur within the initial 6 months of the budgetary period. It is proposed that 570 specimens will be analyzed for 4 metals (Cd, Pb, Hg, As) and speciation of three for about $17 per one of the four metals based upon combined both directs and indirects.

column43: IGF::CT::IGF TASK ORDER ENTITLED,"STRATEGIC DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION PLANNING FOR THE MERIT-BASED INCENTIVE SYSTEM (MIPS) AND RELATED SECTIONS OF MEDICARE ACCESS AND CHIP REAUTHORIZATION ACT".
column45: ALL OTHER PROFESSIONAL, SCIENTIFIC, AND TECHNICAL SERVICES
column67: Contracts and Grants,Educational Institution,Nonprofit Organization,Private University or College
column76:
The Contractor shall provide subject matter expertise to support the research, design, and development of a new Merit-Based Incentive Payment System for CMS.  Contractor shall provide subject matter expertise in: 
   Health care payment systems. Required expertise includes health payment systems design, process improvement, performance transformation of health care departments and agencies, health economics, and financial strategies.  
   Health care analytics. Required expertise includes retrospective claims data analysis, model design, and model simulation. 
   Health care policy research and analysis. Required expertise includes health care policy research and analysis. 
 These experts will participate in teams with MITRE and CMS to support design, policy decisions, and preparation for the deployment of the MIPS. SMEs will contribute to performance of tasks as described below.  
 Merit-Based Incentive Payment System Model Development Using Summary Data 
 Contractor shall work with MITRE, CMS and contractors as appropriate to design the MIPS payment methodology for the first year of the program. The design work requires modeling and simulation to project financial impacts for different performance score and payment adjustment scenarios. The development of the methodology will serve as an input into policy development, and the Contractor shall work closely with the policy team to ensure alignment of the simulation results and policy decisions. 
   Design and execute economic and quality impact simulations based on summary data.  The total number of simulations will be as mutually agreed upon, but is estimated at 8-10 simulations. 
   Define summary data needed from Electronic Health Record Meaningful Use (EHR MU), Physician Quality Reporting System (PQRS) and Physician Value-Based Modifier (VM) programs as well as any other summary claims data needed to support modeling.  
   Develop methodologies to soundly simulate quality impacts and economic impacts from multiple policy and scoring scenarios. The inputs and outputs of the simulations need to be flexible and able to assess both quality and economic impacts.   
   Incorporate the approach to Clinical Practice Improvement Activities (CPIA) and Advancing Care Information developed in Task 3 into the combined scoring methodology model. 
   Define and develop model analysis and design plans. Analyze the information gathered from the MITRE team s stakeholder analysis, communications and policy work potentially including external feedback, technical expert panels (TEP), and stakeholder feedback to validate key assumptions and expected impacts.  
   Report on simulations, document modeling approach, trade-offs and impacts of policy decisions, and recommend a payment methodology approach and/or models for further in-depth analysis. 
   Support analysis and design for selected models and fully document selected models for handoff to CMS or its contractors, including written documentation and fully commented code or spreadsheets. 
 Task 3: Clinical Practice Improvement Activities (CPIA) and Advancing Care Information Model Development  
 Contractor shall work with MITRE, CMS and contractors as appropriate to design an approach to modeling CPIA and Advancing Care Information scoring and impact of alternate approaches within the MIPS payment methodology.  The CPIA and Advancing Care Information scoring forms part of the total scoring methodology being developed in Task 2, which includes the existing programs EHR MU, PQRS, VBM, and includes CPIA as a new assessment. 
 o Define data needed to assess alternate approaches to CPIA and Advancing Care Information scoring, potentially leveraging existing quality improvement mechanisms and data already being reported. Assess alternate data sources if appropriate, including value and impact of using those sources. 
 o Host detailed data in a secure environment in accordance with the CMS DUA. 
 o Define and develop model analysis and design plans. Analyze the info

column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

Task 1: Task Administration
 Task administration activities will be coordinated by the MITRE Project Leader, with input from Contractor. The Contractor shall: 
 1. Participate in meetings and contribute to progress reports throughout the duration of this project, as needed to communicate status, key issues, and findings to CMS.  
 2. Contribute to developing and maintaining a current Project Work Plan, including a detailed timeline of project milestones and deliverables.
 3. Provide a monthly financial report that includes, (1) Inception To Date (ITD) actual costs for work performed (ACWP) for the project, (2) and the contractor s best estimate of the time-phased resources required to complete the remaining authorized work   the Estimate at Complete (EAC).
 4. Invoice MITRE monthly for allowable incurred costs.
 
 Task 2: Lean Expert Consultation
 Provide consultation to MITRE, ThedaCare Center for Healthcare Value and CMS regarding organization-wide approaches to design a lean management system to support the requirements of CMS  operating environment. Attendance of two Senior Lean experts to participate in the CMS Strategy Session for Lean Transformation activities from 31 May-June 3, 2016. John O Donnell and Darlene Dumont are considered key persons identified to participate.

The core activities of the Task Order will be to:
 * Evaluate preliminary key questions, both narrative review and systematic literature review questions Address evidence gaps in key questions
 * Thoroughly examine availability research literature
 * Assess and synthesize evidence available to answer Key Questions Produce a protocol, draft and final report
 * The EPC shall update the report as defined by the questions and with the methods from the original report.
 * The EPC shall host a kick off call with the partner (PCORI).
 * The peer review process shall include a specific review to ensure that the researchhas met all PCORl's Methodoloqv Standards that are relevant to the task
 * The EPC shall document adherence to the Methodology Standards in an Appendix of the report.
 * Report shall be posted to the AHRQ website and PCORI website no later than 90 days after acceptance of the final report.
 
 Gowri Raman, research associate and TBA Research Assistant(s) will collaborate with the Brown EPC team on stakeholder engagement, critically appraise studies, participate in literature screening, data extraction, and perform quantitative data analysis and interpret epidemiological and statistical data, interpret and contextualize partner input, draft and edit final report.

MITRE seeks subject matter expertise to support the research, design, and development of a new Merit-Based
 Incentive Payment System for CMS. MITRE seeks subject matter expertise in:
   Health care payment systems. Required expertise includes health payment systems design, process
 improvement, performance transformation of health care departments and agencies, health
 economics, and financial strategies.
   Health care analytics. Required expertise includes retrospective claims data analysis, model design,
 and model simulation.
   Health care policy research and analysis. Required expertise includes health care policy research
 and analysis.
