column76:
The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD
 
 PHASE 2 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Phase 2 Scope of Work for Base Period
 
 The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.
 
 
 
 Phase 2:
 
 1. The attached work plan represents the aims and work to be carried out by the subcontractor to achieve the project goals.
 2. Subcontractor is required to provide a monthly invoice that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifth of the following month.  First report is due May 5, 2012.  Additional information should be included in the monthly report.  The monthly report format may change if CMS requests additional or different information on the monthly report.  An example monthly report template is attached.
 3. Consistent flow of data in from the Subcontractor s hospitals of at least 80%.
 4. Participation by Subcontractor program personnel at Contractor s national learning activities.
 5. An annual report at the end of 2012 and 2013.

column43: TAS::75 0850::TAS RECOVERY ACT - TISSUE SOURCE SITE (TSS) NETWORKS IN SUPPORT OF THE CANCER GENOME ATLAS (TCGA) PROGRAM
column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations
 o Resource will support Regional Office VSI & RI Events
 
 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.
 
 Task 3: Lean Development Support
 MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in providing lean development support. The Contractor shall:
 
   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource. 
   Specific activities associated with this support include, but are not limited to:
 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.

Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.

 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).

column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

 effectiveness of pharmacotherapy during pregnancy using a variety of study designs and
 data sources, her expertise in epidemiologic methods especially as they relate to
 pregnancy research, and her clinical background. She will be closely involved in the study
 design and protocol development, as well as the study conduct and analyses for each
 aim. Dr. Hernandez-Diaz will contribute her experience in pregnancy research using large
 administrative databases by working closely with Dr. Huybrechts on the creation of the
 analytic datasets for each aim, which will be housed at Brigham and Women's Hospital,
 including any changes to be made to the existing linked mothers/infants dataset. She will
 provide input to the development of the study protocols anddata abstraction forms to be
 used for the medical record review as part of the validation studies; and will critically
 review the final protocol versions and analyses findings. Throughout the project, Dr.
 Hernandez-Diaz will participate in weekly meetings with Dr. Huybrechts and other team members to review the research progress. She will participate in drafting written summaries for inclusion in progress reports to the sponsor, and will help prepare conference presentations and publishable manuscripts.

The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 04/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  Details of the Scope of Work for Phase II will be added to this Agreement by written amendment signed by the Parties (the  Phase 2 SOW Amendment ).  A separate Scope of Work will be provided to Subcontractor prior to expiration of the Base Period if Contractor exercises the Option Period.  
 
 The guaranteed funding for Phase 1 of the Subcontractor s effort is a single up front lump sum payment of $50,000 U.S. Dollars, payable within thirty (30) business days of execution of this Agreement.  During Phase 1, Subcontractor will also be eligible for an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of delivery of the Subcontractor s list of participating hospitals and the commitment letters.  Phase 2 funding will be made available according to a schedule of deliverables and payments as specified in the Phase 2 SOW Amendment.  The Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding is $TBD U.S. Dollars.  Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the Phase 1 and Phase 2 tasks and deliverables in excess of these amounts.  
 
 PHASE 1 TASKS:
 
 1. Distribute  Needs Assessment Survey  (supplied by Contractor in early 01/2012) to participating hospitals no later than 01/2102/24/2012.
 2. Ensure completion rate of at least 85% of participating hospitals.
 3. Analyze With HRET, analyze results of  Needs Assessment Surveys  
 4. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan and budget shall cover two time periods (1) remainder of 2012, and (2) calendar 2013.  The total budget shall be less than the Phase 2 not-to-exceed funding amount set out above.  Subcontractor shall consult with Contractor on the proposed plan and budget.  
 5. [__]
 
 PHASE 1 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Final Llist of hospitals committed to work with Subcontractor as well as copies of hospital commitment letters.  Due 01/05131/2012.  
 2. Completed  Needs Assessment Survey  results to Contractor.  Due 02/1424/2012.  
 3. Draft work plan and budget for performing Phase II.  Work plan must include an event or improvement activity to be conducted by 04/06/2012.  Due 03/0115/2012. 
 4. Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month, and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; and (2) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  Due by the fifteenth of the following month (first report due 0304/15/2012 for month of FebruaryMarch).  
 5. Executed amendments to the Agreement adding final Phase II Scope of Work.  Due 04/01/2012.  
 
 PHASE 2 TASKS:
 
 1. TBD

Subcontractor is required to provide monthly progress reports that: (1) identify the individuals performing work on behalf of Subcontractor, the hours worked by each such individual during the previous month and a statement of expenses incurred in performance of the work during the previous month; (2) include a discussion of effort spent in comparison to the work plan and budget and (3) discuss the work completed during the previous month.  The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services ( CMS ) awarded Prime Contract No. HHSM-500-2012-00017C to Contractor to implement the Partnership for Patients ( PFP ), a priority project designed to reduce inpatient harm by 40% and readmissions by 20% over a 3 year period.  Contractor, in turn, engaged Subcontractor to perform the tasks and provide the deliverables described below and in support of its requirements under the Prime Contract.  
 
 Period of Performance:  This Base Period Scope of Work is divided into two phases.  Phase 1 will cover Subcontractor s performance through 05/01/2012.  Phase 2 will cover the remainder of the Base Period.  
 
 Insurance:  During performance of this Agreement, Subcontractor shall maintain the following minimum levels of insurance:  Workers Compensation (as required by applicable law); Automobile Liability ($200,000 U.S. Dollars per person and $500,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence); and (Overall 
 Liability (with aggregate general or umbrella policies of at least $2,000,000 U.S. Dollars per occurrence).  
 
 Funding for Phase 2:  The guaranteed funding for Phase 2 of the Subcontractor s effort consists of 21 equal monthly payments of U.S. Dollars.  Contractor will strive to pay proper invoices within thirty (30) days of receipt by Contractor, and payments will be made via Contractor s EFT/ACH payment process.  Subcontractor shall provide all the necessary EFT/ACH payment information upon the request of Contractor.  Subcontractor will also receive an additional $1,000 U.S. Dollars per committed hospital to be paid by Subcontractor to the hospital to offset the hospital s data collection costs.  A lump sum of these offset payments will be paid to Subcontractor within thirty (30) business days of this signed amendment
 
 This is a firm fixed price agreement.  Subcontractor is required to perform all of the obligations contained in this Agreement at the aforementioned price.  No additional amounts will be paid unless specifically agreed to in writing by Contractor.  
 
 Pre-existing Subcontractor Intellectual Property:  The Parties acknowledge that Subcontractor is entering into this Agreement with pre-existing Intellectual Property Rights.

column76: The team at Subcontractor #1 shall continue to provide a pool of potential study participants who are receiving homogenous irradiation to their teeth as part of therapeutic total body irradiation (TBI). This population, who have received prescribed homogeneous (and known) doses at a level appropriate to model exposures from nuclear events, are uniquely qualified to provide accurate models of the situation for which the technology is aimed: after-the-fact determination of exposure to radiation of levels that could lead to the acute radiation syndrome. The capabilities of the instruments developed by the Prime Contractor and engineering subcontractors will be evaluated using study participants recruited from patients of Subcontractor #1 who are receiving or have received radiation doses in the pertinent dose range, through measurements made at the site of Subcontractor #1 or at the site of the Prime Contractor, by referral from Subcontractor #1 for measurements in patients who previously completed therapy, if this is more convenient for the patient.   Using these groups of human subjects, data will be obtained that will aid in the development of appropriate calibration curves, using in vivo EPR directly in the populations of interest, using the devices specifically designed for such use.  The measurements will be made by operators who are part of the irradiating facility who have received training and ongoing support by the Prime Contractor.

Abt Associates will provide staff and time to accomplish the following activities:
 1. Co-lead the development of the program course design guide and the companion implementation manual for facilities.  
 1.  Abt will co-lead the development of draft and final versions of the course design guide, which will address curriculum topic, educational format and delivery mechanisms. Abt will also have co-lead responsibilities for writing companion CAUTI-LTC implmentation manuals that will summarize the program's technical and cultural interventions addressed in the course design materials. Abt will also co-lead the content and materials development subcommittee of this project.
 2.  Support the development of the CAUTI-LTC Toolkit.  Abt will support the development of the customizable toolkit, shaing any relevant pre-existing materials to the personnel leading this effort, and offering ongoing feedback on the draft versions of the toolkit.  The content and materials development subcommittee will inform and review draft and final versions of the toolkit (educational modules with trigger videos, slide decks and facilitatior notes).
 3.  Provide consulting services as needed.  Abt will provide consulting services around the toolkit, project content and curriculum throughout the course of the project on an as needed basis in order to meet the requirements of the project deliverables and activties for Year 1.
 4.  Support the implementation of the program in LTC facilities by serving as faculty on national calls and webinars, at local or regional in-person meetings, and at master training events.  Abt staff will function as faculty as needed on a limited number of national conference calls and/or webinars, and potentially in one in-person state-based or regional meeting.  Abt staff will also serve as faculty at master training events for other faculty HRET will recruit during the course of the project.
 5. Support the assessment of program impact.  Abt staff will support efforts to ensure that data collection protocols and participant reports are tailored to the needs of LTC staff participating in the project.  Abt will designate a team member to serve on the measurement and evaluation subcommittee.  In addition, Abt will recommend to the measurement and evaluation subcommittee the metrics and data collection methods most appropriate for the LTC setting.
 6. Administer the project at Abt.  Abt will designate an individual on their team who will coordinate with HRET on all Abt activities and deliverables. Abt staff will provide monthly reports and other information needed for HRET to meet its contractual obligations.

column76: An emerging set of technologies, based on mass spectrometry, enable the monitoring of hundreds of metabolites from biological samples. These technologies have promise to transform our ability to profile samples with the goals of illuminating pathophysiology and discovering valuable clinical biomarkers. The Broad Institute has established a mass spectrometry-based metabolite profiling platform that presently targets approximately 300 metabolites, of which several hundred are measurable in mammalian cells and human serum. Dr. Clary Clish serves as a PI and the Director of this platform. In the proposed studies, the Broad platform will be used to comprehensively analyze 2860 human plasma samples toward discovery of metabolic indicators of coronary heart disease (CHD) in women.  This number includes 3729 plasma samples from CHD cases, controls and QC specimens. These metabolite profiling efforts will include preparing samples for analyses using several LC-MS methods for each sample, acquiring the LC-MS data, data processing, and reporting results to the PI and co-investigators. Dr. Clish will collaborate with the BWH team on analysis and interpretation of metabolomic data, and will participate in the writing and critical review of manuscripts.

column76: The goal of the proposed research is to determine whether three different micro-engineered  organ-on-chip  microphysiological systems (Gut Chip, Bone Marrow Chip and Lung Chip) can serve as in vitro alternatives to in vivo screening of Medical Countermeasures (MCMs) for Acute Radiation Syndrome. In Phase 1 (24 months) of the Base Period (42 months), we will begin studies with a human Gut Chip that contains living human intestinal epithelial cells cultured within microfluidic devices that recapitulate the three- dimensional (3D) villus architecture and mechanically active microenvironment of the living intestine. Radiation sensitivity and MCM studies will be carried out using the gut chip in the presence or absence of a living microbiome. In addition, we will carry out experiments using a Bone Marrow Chip that is formed by engineering whole artificial bone in a living mouse, and then removing it and culturing it within a microfluidic device. Although we will begin with mouse marrow, we also will carry out studies to explore if we can replace the mouse marrow cells with cells from human cord blood to create a human Bone Marrow Chip.

Support the design, creation and enhancement of improvement resources required under the contract, including resources for participating facilities and for connector organizations working with these facilities.  Resources will include change packages (in electronic or print forms), Powerpoint presentations for use in meetings and on webinars, and video vignettes used to illustrate improvement concepts.

column43: NATIONAL IMPLEMENTATION OF COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CATHETER-ASSOCIATED URINARY TRACT INFECTION (CAUTI)
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE SOCIAL SCIENCES AND HUMANITIES
column76:
Scope of Work 
 
 In August 2011, AHRQ sought to deploy and implement a program for the support and expansion of the adoption and use of a CUSP that can be applied to reduce CAUTI in hospitals in all States, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico through State-based or regional consortia/collaborative in a phased approach.  This work builds upon and expands the current activities to demonstrate the effectiveness of CUSP for CAUTI in twelve States.  This follow-on effort utilizes the resources and materials for CUSP for CAUTI that have been developed as part of earlier contract work for this expansion of the national implementation effort.  
 
 The total funding for Subcontractor s effort is $20,000 U.S. Dollars in the Base Year and $50,000 in the Option Year. Subcontractor is solely responsible for any costs for completion of the following tasks and deliverables in excess of this amount.  
 
 TASKS:
 
 1. Ensure the recruitment and continued active participation of at least 10 hospitals in the project.
 2. Obtain and maintain general knowledge of the project (goals, expectations, interventions, timelines, schedules, etc.) and serve as a liaison between the national project team and hospital units.
 3. Work with unit teams to assist with culture improvements and overcoming project barriers.
 4. Provide individual coaching with identified high outliers.
 5. Regularly participate in scheduled calls with the national project team and encourage participating hospitals to do the same.
 6. Work with extended faculty to develop specific state curriculum needs.
 7. Commit to the goal of reducing mean CAUTI rates in participating clinical units by 25 percent, and improving safety culture as evidenced by improved teamwork and communication by employing CUSP methodology.  
 
 DELIVERABLES:
 
 1. Provide a part-time project coordinator to function as the state lead.
 2. Monitor and coordinate with participating hospitals to assure their submission of:
 a. Monthly infection rate data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 b. AHRQ Safety Culture surveys at the beginning and end of the project
 c. Quarterly team check up tool data that is current and 70% complete (or improving)
 3. Submit the State Lead Monthly Status Report (Attachment E).
 4. Facilitate monthly coaching calls and establish agendas for them.
 5. Coordinate three face-to-face learning sessions (at the start of the project, at mid-collaborative, and at the end of the collaborative).
 6. Coordinate site visits to units as needed.

column43: TAS::75 0850::TAS RECOVERY ACT - TISSUE SOURCE SITE (TSS) NETWORKS IN SUPPORT OF THE CANCER GENOME ATLAS (TCGA) PROGRAM
column54: BRIGHAM AND WOMEN'S HOSPITAL, INC., THE
column76:
The CALGB Group Chair's Office will be responsible for overseeing the work done by CALGB institutions and issuing appropriate payments for the completed work.  In order to complete the payments, data will be needed from the CALGB data management center, lung cancer tissue bank and Washington University.  
 
 Each site will be led by a clinician who acts as the principal investigator and who has direct access to potentially eligible patients.  A clinical research assistant (CRA) will provide administrative support for IRB approval and help clinicians in re-consenting patients.  
 
 In consultation with the site clinicians, pathologists and tumor bank director, we have established firm guidelines on how to collect the tumor specimens for this project. Efforts were made to get the  meat of the tumor  right after the necessary diagnostic specimens are obtained in the operating room. This process will ensure that tumor nuclei rich material is harvested for the TSS project. Furthermore, the pathologist working with the director of the tumor bank or the tumor bank director will review the collected material to ensure that only cases that meet the criteria set forth by the disease working group are sent out to BCR. While it would be ideal to achieve a near 100% acceptance rate of the samples sent out to BCR, we do recognize that there may be discrepancies and not all tumors that passed through a stringent review at the repository may be acceptable to BCR.

column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

Media Campaign/Visual Design Support 
 The Contractor shall provide graphics design development support for the CMS Interoperability Initiative and the associated media campaign. In addition to development activities, the Contractor shall participate in planned working sessions with CMS personnel and other members of the MITRE delivery team to assist in creating impactful and accurate materials to communicate strategy and methodology, and to create templates which may be used by the team for ongoing activities and communications.
 
 Working sessions may be by phone or in person as needed. 
 
 The Contractor shall support ongoing and iterative creation of designs that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns to best represent the Interoperability Initiative strategy and methodology. These concept designs shall be developed at the direction of the MITRE Project Leader  or Designee.
 
 After MITRE has reviewed the concept designs, the Contractor shall generate mockups/drafts, delivered in the format defined by the MITRE, via email to the MITRE Project Leader or Designee.
 
 The Contractor shall:
 1) Work as an integrated team with MITRE, Alliance Partners, and Subcontractors.
 2) Participate in work sessions and other meetings to review recommendations and develop presentation materials, including updates to the CMS Interoperability Road Map.
 3) Design a communications and branding strategy related to the MyHealthEData initiative and the interoperability proposed rule.
 4) At the discretion of the Project Leader, assist in development of communications materials, graphics designs, branding, and coordinating with CMS on ad hoc basis.
 5) Ensure all materials delivered under contract meet Federal Government 508 Compliance standards, consistent with CMS style guides.
 6) Ensure all materials and methods used are free from licensing/fee payments, copyrights, and trademarks.

MITRE requires external support from the Contractor in conducting value stream improvement initiatives and rapid improvement events. The Contractor shall:
 
   Central Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 2 initiatives, each with up to 5 individual events
 o Resource should be located within 50 miles from Central Office location
 o Resource will support Central Office Value Stream Improvement (VSI) and Rapid Improvement Events (RI) Events
 
   Regional Office Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event Consultation 
 o Up to 1 initiative, with up to 5 individual events 
 o Resource(s) should be able to travel or located near Regional Office locations
 o Resource will support Regional Office VSI & RI Events
 
 Specific activities associated with these events include, but are not limited to:
 1. Confirming CISPS intake process is performed per standard work
 2. Consulting with and interviewing stakeholders to develop problem statement and business case. 
 3. Facilitating session to complete an event charter.
 4. Collecting and analyzing data including capturing data related to ROI. 
 5. Capturing mother and child value stream maps in electronic format, to include both current state and future state.  
 6. Developing action/implementation plans with timelines and milestones that correspond with the Improvement Approach phases and includes expected performance measures.  
 7. Creating a data collection/analysis plan for all measures that includes, but not limited to, data source/location, collection method, who will collect the data, and how the data will be represented (etc. pareto chart, histogram).
 8. Tracking and regularly reporting on progress towards achieving targets and closing performance gaps. 
 9. Coaching and mentoring CMS Lean Leads and CISPS who are facilitating VSIs in the VSI process using CMS developed methods/processes.
 10. Updating standard work documenting how to conduct events.
 11. Developing and implementing a plan to transition the VSI work to the appropriate party, as directed by CISPS. 
 
 CISPS, MITRE, and the Contractor shall establish methodologies for assessing potential improvement activities, including leveraging the CISPS intake process to prioritize events. Once a final decision is made by CISPS, the Contractor shall establish a charter that specifies the participants, problem statement, business case, scope, responsibilities, timeframe for completion of the activity(s), and any ongoing performance measures for measuring the success of the activity(s). Once the charter is approved by CISPS, the Contractor shall allocate resources to implement improvement activities that would meet the expectations and deliverables set forth in the charter. 
 
 All electronic correspondence with the customer in support of the above-mentioned activities shall include a designated MITRE resource. All improvement activities shall be tracked as part of the monthly Process Improvement Report (VSI Tracker) and shall inform other CMS administrative reports, including the MITRE Monthly Progress Report. The Contractor is responsible for tracking the logistics, planning, level of effort, and costs for each Value Stream Improvement and Rapid Improvement Event.

   Provide up to 2 months of Lean Development Support (0.5 to 1.0 resource), working in combination with an assigned MITRE lean support resource.

 1. Continued development of an internal capacity for facilitating and coaching Lean methodologies (e.g., Lean Ambassador, Lean Leads and Managers as Coaches) in order to position CMS to achieve efficiencies, reduce variation across components, and apply standard work as fundamental to process improvements.

column76: Dr. Sharpe's group is analyzing aged-related changes in CD8 T cell responses in  mice in close collaboration with Drs. Marcia Haigis and E. John Wherry. Dr Haigis group studies the role of sirtuins in the metabolic regulation of T cell responses in young and aged mice. The main goals of their studies are understand how sirtuins regulate (1) the role of key metabolic pathways in immune regulation, and  (2) to test the hypothesis that immune senescence can be attributed, at least partially, to metabolic malfunction.

column76: The team at Subcontractor #1 shall continue to provide a pool of potential study participants who are receiving homogenous irradiation to their teeth as part of therapeutic total body irradiation (TBI). This population, who have received prescribed homogeneous (and known) doses at a level appropriate to model exposures from nuclear events, are uniquely qualified to provide accurate models of the situation for which the technology is aimed: after-the-fact determination of exposure to radiation of levels that could lead to the acute radiation syndrome. The capabilities of the instruments developed by the Prime Contractor and engineering subcontractors will be evaluated using study participants recruited from patients of Subcontractor #1 who are receiving or have received radiation doses in the pertinent dose range, through measurements made at the site of Subcontractor #1 or at the site of the Prime Contractor, by referral from Subcontractor #1 for measurements in patients who previously completed therapy, if this is more convenient for the patient.   Using these groups of human subjects, data will be obtained that will aid in the development of appropriate calibration curves, using in vivo EPR directly in the populations of interest, using the devices specifically designed for such use.  The measurements will be made by operators who are part of the irradiating facility who have received training and ongoing support by the Prime Contractor.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF ORDER FOR SERVICES "OTHER FUNCTIONS" - TASK ORDER #0008 TECHNICAL SUPPORT FOR EPA'S TOOL TO ESTIMATE EMISSIONS FROM CLEAN ENERGY
column76:
The Subcontractor will provide support to EPA in the following work areas, which fall under the
 responsibility of the programs in the Climate Protection Partnerships Division:
 1. Tool completion and maintenance: The focus of this work area will be Subcontractor support
 for the draft Statistical Displaced Emissions Model s (SDEM) design, functionality, usability,
 maintenance and marketability.
 2. Documentation: The focus of this work area will be Subcontractor support in completing the
 documentation, user guide and supplemental documents for the SDEM.
 3. Technical Assistance: The focus of this work area will be Subcontractor support in providing
 technical assistance for EPA and other stakeholders to properly use SDEM and other clean energy
 related emissions analysis.
 Task 1   Task Order Administration
 This task includes administrative activities necessary for carrying out the work under this statement of
 work, including monthly progress reports and budget discussions with the EPA Contracting Officer s
 Representative (COR). The Subcontractor shall work with ERG to maintain and promote lines of
 communication including check-in and deliverables meetings for all tasks and subtasks. At the request of
 either the government, ERG, or the Subcontractor, meetings shall be held to discuss the overall progress
 on the task order, or to resolve conflicts or other issues that may arise in the implementation of work
 under this contract. When needed, these discussions will normally be conducted via conference call.
 However, the government reserves the right to hold in-person meetings in Washington, D.C.
 The Subcontractor will also perform tracking activities so it can respond to requests for information from
 the government and from ERG concerning issues of task order management, i.e., overall progress on the
 contract, trouble-shooting, and other task order-level issues. As specified in written technical direction
 issued by the COR, the Subcontractor shall address specific issues or provide non-routine type data or
 information to aid in tracking performance under this contract.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF  CREATING A CULTURE OF CONTINUOUS QUALITY IMPROVEMENT IN CHILD CARE AND HEAD START SETTINGS
column45: ADMINISTRATIVE MANAGEMENT AND GENERAL MANAGEMENT CONSULTING SERVICES
column67: Educational Institution,State Controlled Institution of Higher Learning,U.S. State Government
column76:
During Year 2 University of Massachusetts-Boston (UMB) shall provide the following services:
 Anne Douglass and her team at UMB will manage the overall implementation of the Breakthrough Series Collaborative (BSC) with child care centers and Head Start programs around the Boston area. 
 For the implementation of the CQI intervention (task 8), UMB will develop and finalize a measurement system, coach and prep the project team, conduct a one-and-a-half-day orientation and training for faculty and project staff; conduct readiness activities with the selected sites, begin learning sessions at the launch of implementation, and oversee and ensure action periods are fully executed. 
 UMB will work closely with Quality Improvement Consultants, serve as main point of contact for ECE programs, manage site outreach and selection, coordinate Learning Sessions, conference calls, and quality metrics collection, tracks teams  and overall CCCQI BSC progress and manages/provides coaching to Core Teams (task 8). 
 UMB staff will assist the implementation team with all aspects of the planning and implementation of the BSC, including providing onsite support and coaching to ECE teams at each program site (task 8). 
 As a part of the implementation plan design, UMB will recruit and hire quality improvement consultants, as needed, and recruit and hire 2-5 content experts in social and emotional learning (task 8). 
 In partnership with Child Trends, UMB will submit a list of candidate sites to the COR and make the final selection (task 7). 
 UMB will also develop and submit a site exploration and selection and lesson learned summary memo to the COR (task 7). 
 To prepare for the CQI intervention implementation, UMB will invite 10-12 ECE programs to apply for participation in the BSC or similar intervention through a process that includes calls or meetings with each applicant; 8 sites will be selected for participation in the intervention (task 7).

column43: UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT, THE OFFICE OF WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (OWM) WORKS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH EPA REGIONS, SATES AND TRIBES TO REGULATE DISCHARGES, AS DEFINED UNDER THE ACT, INTO APPLICABLE SURFACE WATERS, SUCH AS WETLANDS, LAKES, RIVERS, ESTUARIES, BAYS AND OCEANS. TYPICALLY OWM FOCUSES ON WATER THAT COLLECTS IN DISCRETE CONVEYANCES OR POINT SOURCES, TO INCLUDE WATER THAT COLLECTS IN PIPES, DITCHES, AND SANITARY OR STORM SEWERS. THIS METHODOLOGY OF ANALYZING IDENTIFIABLE POINT SOURCES WITHIN A DEFINED WATERSHED IS INTENDED TO MAXIMIZE CONTINUITY IN SOLUTION TO ADDRESS ALL POLLUTION PROBLEMS WITHIN A DEFINITIVE GEOGRAPHIC AREA. AGAIN, TARGETING POINT SOURCES OF POLLUTION, NATURAL OR OTHERWISE, A WATERSHED-BASED NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES) IS A BASIS TO QUALIFY AND MEASURE ALTERNATIVES THROUGH THE DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY SOUND PERMITS FOR MULTIPLE POINT SOURCES LOCATED WITHIN A WATERSHED SO AS TO EFFECTIVELY MEET WATER QUALITY STANDARDS.   IN ADDITION, OWM REQUIRES SUPPORT IN THE DIRECTION AND PROMOTION OF THE PROGRAMS CONDUCTED UNDER THE CLEAN WATER STATE REVOLVING FUND, THE LARGEST SINGLE WATER QUALITY-FUNDING SOURCE, WHOSE EMPHASIS FOCUSES ON FUNDING WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEMS, NONPOINT SOURCE PROJECTS, AND ESTUARY PROTECTION. IN MEETING THESE MISSION REQUIREMENTS, OWM REQUIRES TECHNICAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES TO QUANTIFY AND EXTEND THE BASE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SPECIALIZED EXPERTISE NECESSARY FOR DECISION-MAKERS TO FULFILL THEIR STATUTORY RESPONSIBILITIES.  THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) SHALL PRESENT THE SCOPE OF THOSE AREAS OF SUPPORT AND TECHNICAL EXPERIENCE THAT ARE REQUIRED BY OWM. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE CONTRACT CLAUSE, WORK ASSIGNMENTS (EPAAR 1552.211-74), EPA SHALL PROVIDE THE CONTRACTOR WITH SPECIFIC PERIODIC REQUIREMENTS UNDER SPECIFIC, INDIVIDUAL WORK ASSIGNMENTS ISSUED FOR SERVICES DURING THE PERFORMANCE PERIODS OF THIS CONTRACT.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPPORT SERVICES UNDER THIS PERFORMANCE WORK STATEMENT (PWS) WILL PARALLEL OWM'S PROGRAM RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THE CLEAN WATER ACT (CWA) AND THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT (SDWA), TO INCLUDE SERVICES IN SUPPORT FOR THE NATIONAL POLLUTANT DISCHARGE ELIMINATION SYSTEM (NPDES), BOTH MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL DISCHARGES FROM STORM WATER, SEWER SYSTEM OVERFLOWS, CONSTRUCTION, COMMERCIAL VESSELS, AND ANIMAL FEEDING OPERATIONS. IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE SUPPORT SERVICES FOR EPA ACTIONS PURSUANT TO THE CLEAN WATER ACT, SECTION 316 [COOLING WATER INTAKE], THE NATIONAL PRETREATMENT PROGRAM, THE CLEAN WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING LOAN FUND, THE SAFE DRINKING WATER ACT STATE REVOLVING FUND, AND THE NATIONAL BIOSOLIDS PROGRAM.   UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHALL THIS CONTRACT BE USED AS A VEHICLE TO CHANNEL FUNDS TO ASSISTANCE RECIPIENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL SERVICES, TO INCLUDE ALL SUPPLIES, FACILITIES, AND EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO PERFORM AND AFFECT THE REQUIRED PERFORMANCE WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THIS PWS IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND REGULATIONS, FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL.

Model Scoring Methodology Options for the NGACO Model
 The final set(s) of measures will need some high-level analysis of options for a scoring methodology that will define how NGACO participant may be scored on the quality measures. This methodology may include options about how the quality scores will impact NGACO payments to participants. The Contractor shall carry out the following in a timely manner:
 1. Participate in planning sessions with the Sponsor and the MITRE model team, as requested.
 2. Provide expert guidance on measure scoring methodologies, benchmarking, and other factors related to the implementation and evaluation of quality measures. 
 3. Conduct further research and analysis, as needed, related to scoring methodologies.
 4. Provide written contributions to related documents such as memo(s) that provide options for a scoring methodology, along with an analysis of strengths and weaknesses.
 5. Provide assistance as needed with reviewing documentation, including timely and constructive review of the outline, subsequent drafts, and the final version.
 
 Additional Policy, Research and Operational Analysis in support of the NGACO model
 Other tasking may be associated with the measure selection for the NGACO model. For example, as part of the measure selection work CMMI has asked for a Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) which will, at a minimum, document NGACO s process for selecting a new measure set and related best practices. In addition, written materials and additional analyses may be required as measures undergo clearance, e.g., development of an Innovation Center Investment Plan (ICIP) modification. The Contractor shall carry out the following in a timely manner as specified by MITRE:
 1. Participate in planning sessions with the Sponsor and the MITRE model team, as requested.
 2. Provide expert guidance in planning policy research, operational approaches, and additional research to aid in model design, roll out, and implementation decisions.
 3. Provide assistance as needed with conducting the research and developing options for approaches.
 4. Provide written contributions to the documents or draft documents, such as an SOP or ICIP modification, as needed.
 5. Provide assistance as needed with reviewing documentation, including timely and constructive review of the outline, subsequent drafts, and the final version.

Support Refinements to the ACO Regulations
 The Contractor shall carry out work designed to support future refinements to ACO regulations and risk adjustment.  The central goal is to better understand savings opportunities, profitability of ACO participation from the perspective of providers, as well as how to design regulations to promote ACO success and program savings. For the first period of performance, the Contractor shall:
 
 1. Participate in planning sessions with the Sponsor and the MITRE model team, as requested.
 2. Use Medicare claims data to understand variation in ACO spending patterns and assess what services high-spending ACOs use (and for what patients and episodes) relative to low spending ACOs (after risk adjustment), and to examine changes in risk scores for different organizations, some of which will be ACOs, others will be  pseudo ACOs  made up of large organizations eligible for ACO participation but not part of the program. 
 3. To support policy recommendations, conduct a qualitative assessment to understand how ACO leaders view how certain aspects of policies such as internal financial modeling and risk tolerance influence ACO participation and profitability. 
 Additional Policy, Research and Operational Analysis in support of the ACO model
 Other tasking may be required of the contractor for the ACO model.  The Contractor shall carry out the following in a timely manner as specified by MITRE:
 
 1. Take primary responsibility for providing expert guidance to CMMI, and work closely with the MITRE team, in planning policy research, operational approaches, and additional research to aid in model design, roll out, and implementation decisions.
 2. Take primary responsibility, and work closely with the MITRE team, to conducting the research and developing options for approaches.
 3. Provide written contributions to the documents or draft documents, such as an Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) or ICIP modification, as needed.

column76: Dr. Sharpe's group is analyzing aged-related changes in CD8 T cell responses in  mice in close collaboration with Drs. Marcia Haigis and E. John Wherry. Dr Haigis group studies the role of sirtuins in the metabolic regulation of T cell responses in young and aged mice. The main goals of their studies are understand how sirtuins regulate (1) the role of key metabolic pathways in immune regulation, and  (2) to test the hypothesis that immune senescence can be attributed, at least partially, to metabolic malfunction.

column43: IGF::OT::IGF NATIONAL IMPLEMENTATION OF COMPREHENSIVE UNIT-BASED SAFETY PROGRAM (CUSP) TO REDUCE CATHETER-ASSOCIATED URINARY TRACT INFECTION (CAUTI) IN LONG TERM CARE FACILITIES
column45: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE SOCIAL SCIENCES AND HUMANITIES
column76:
1. Ensure the recruitment of at least 10 long term care facilities throughout the duration of the twelve-month project participation period.  It is highly recommeded that 15 LTCFs are recruited at the beginning stages of the project to ensure retention of the required 10 LTCFs.  Retention is defined as all 10 facilities submitting monthly data that are current and have a data submission rate of at least 70% or higher.
 2.  Obtain and maintain general knowledge of the project (goals, expectations, interventions, timelines, schedules, etc) and serve as a liaison between the national program team and the LTCFs.
 3.  Encourage all LTCF team members to complete the two safety culture survey administrations (baseline and near project close), and assist with safety culture improvements and overcoming program barriers by adopting techniques discussed on national content calls related to safety culture.
 4. Monitor LTCFs's monthly data reports provided by HRET, and advise LTCFs with outlier results or low data submission rates to participate in office hours to improve performance.
 5.  Participate along with at least one team member from each LTCF (more team members are preferred) on all educational webinars and conference calls.  Encourage LTCF team members unable to listen to the live webinar or conference call to view or listen to an archived webinars and conference calls.
 6.  Commit to the AHRQ's Safety Program for Long Term Care change package intervention, which includes: a. Evidence-based infection and complication prevention practices; b. Improved safety culture through the adaptation of the proven safety program known as CUSP. 
 Deliverable 1:  Hire, assign or delegate a part-time project coordinator to function as the state consortium lead for the 12 month project implemenation period; recruit a minimun of 10 facilities into the program by August 29, 2014; attend two pre-training webinars and a one day in person Consortium Lead training with HRET and members of the NPT in Chicago; and send weeekly updates and email reminders to Facility Leads that are provided by HRET about educational calls and events, data collection and reporting as well as other important program updates.
 Deliverable 2: Part 1 - Coordinate and attend state/regional kick-off, midcourse and final in person or virutal meeting.  Attend monthly Consortium Lead calls with HRET and other members of the NPT to address challenges and successes.  Part 2 - Monitor and coordinate with each participating LTCF to ensure that monthly data that are current and that their data submission rate is at least 70% or higher.  Data that must be submitted include project readiness assessment, culture asssement; ongoing submission of a least 1 outcome and 1 process measure related to the prevention of CAUTIs and ongoing project assessments.  Part 3 - Review performance of participating LTCFs encourage LTCFs with identified opportunities for improvement to attend national office hours and to consult with higher performing LTCFs in the state or region or HRET referred national Subject Matter Experts.  The Lead Organization has retained a minimum of 10 facilites throughout the duration of the project period, as defined by all 10 facilities throughout the duration of the project period, as defined by all 10 faciltites submitting monthly data that are current and have a data submission rate of at least 70% or higher

column76: The goal of the proposed research is to determine whether three different micro-engineered  organ-on-chip  microphysiological systems (Gut Chip, Bone Marrow Chip and Lung Chip) can serve as in vitro alternatives to in vivo screening of Medical Countermeasures (MCMs) for Acute Radiation Syndrome. In Phase 1 (24 months) of the Base Period (42 months), we will begin studies with a human Gut Chip that contains living human intestinal epithelial cells cultured within microfluidic devices that recapitulate the three- dimensional (3D) villus architecture and mechanically active microenvironment of the living intestine. Radiation sensitivity and MCM studies will be carried out using the gut chip in the presence or absence of a living microbiome. In addition, we will carry out experiments using a Bone Marrow Chip that is formed by engineering whole artificial bone in a living mouse, and then removing it and culturing it within a microfluidic device. Although we will begin with mouse marrow, we also will carry out studies to explore if we can replace the mouse marrow cells with cells from human cord blood to create a human Bone Marrow Chip.

column76:
The Sickle Cell Disease Treatment Demonstration Program (SCDTDP) provides grants to regional networks that will work with primary care practices that treat Sickle Cell Disease, comprehensive Sickle Cell Disease centers, and community-based support organizations to provide coordinated, comprehensive, culturally competent, and family-centered care to families with Sickle Cell Disease.
 
 To address these barriers to access to sickle cell disease care, the Maternal and Child Health Bureau (MCHB) is adjusting the SCDTDP to a regional model.  The regional approach has been used by MCHB with other programs and will increase the reach of the program to provide access to a greater number of patients.  
 
 The purpose of this procurement for the SCDTDP Coordinating Center is to obtain services to gather data from and evaluate the performance of the SCDTDP grantees in addressing the three goals of the program, including: 1) increasing the number of providers treating persons for sickle cell disease for sickle cell related issues; 2) increasing the number of providers prescribing disease modifying therapies such as hydroxyurea; and 3) increasing the number of sickle cell patients that are receiving regular care with providers knowledgeable about treating sickle cell disease.  
 
 The contractor will be responsible for supporting data collection and reporting results of the SCDTDP as follows during the course of the Base Year and Option Years 1 and 2:
 
   Create a database with data elements and a data dictionary that allows HRSA to collect and evaluate data from multiple regions on meeting the goals of the program
   Contribute to and implement from and informatics perspective reporting strategies that allow HRSA to report results of the program to the general public
   Contribute to a Report to Congress on the SCDTDP

Statement of Work:
 The following tasks have been identified:
 1. Aim 1: Produce a coding and non-coding annotation and analysis pipeline that can be applied to an array of heart, lung, and blood traits to identify candidate causal variants for functional validation.
 a. Annotate variants in coding regions using LOFTEE (github.com/konradjk/loftee), a custom annotation tool developed at the Broad Institute as a plugin for Ensembl's Variant Effect Predictor.
 b. Build catalog of putative functional elements in relevant tissues. Catalogs of functional elements using publically available data and data from collaborators.
 2. Aim 2: Carry out primary association analyses within these sequence data to identify genetic variants associated with CHD and its quantitative risk factors as well as blood cell traits.
 a. Carry out single-variant association analysis of continuous measures or comparing cases to controls.
 b. Identify functional categories enriched for trait-associated variants. Test variants annotated to various functional categories for evidence of enrichment in trait- or disease-associated variants.
 c. Conduct multiple-variant aggregation association analysis.
 d. Depending on the size and numbers of elements within an enriched annotation category, test (1) within single annotation elements (if the element is long enough to include multiple variants), and/or (2) within all annotation elements genome-wide (if the elements are small and/or not too numerous).
 e. Carry out aggregation tests using genotypes based on sequencing data, including covariates of age, sex, and genotype-based principal components.
  Performance requirements/Deliverables 
 1. Conference calls once 1-2 months with the JHS leadership team (Drs. A. Correa and/or J. Wilson) to report on progress on the SOW. 
 2. Manuscript on identification of candidate functional variants affecting CHD and its risk factors; 
 3. Manuscript on identification of candidate functional variants affecting blood cell traits; 
 4. Deposition of all sequence data and (cross-cohort) harmonized phenotypes in dbGaP.

column76:
A.  Sampling & Recruitment of Provider Practice Locations
 Clark will continue to provide technical support to PBS for the enumeration and subsequent characterization of provider-practice locations.  Specifically, Clark will work closely with the selected provider-practices (post-sampling) to fully characterize the catchment areas where eligible women reside using coarse-scale patient zip-code data and extant environmental and social data (see Study Data Collection).  This activity will expand on methods developed in previous NCS stratification work (Downs et al. 2010a).  This activity will be designed such that it meets and exceeds human subjects and privacy requirements, and is an activity that benefits both the NCS Study Team and the participating provider-practice.  Prior experience of community-based participatory research (CBPR, see Downs et al. 2010b, 2010c, 2009) has shown us the value of sharing the benefits   as well as the costs   of health research, and that the benefits should significantly outweigh the costs for all participants, including providers, and especially patients.
 B. Recruitment and Enrollment of Eligible Women
 Clark will assist UMMS in the design, testing, implementation and monitoring of recruitment methods tailored to local conditions, with cultural and socio-economic sensitivity (e.g. appropriate language and literacy levels for different socio-demographic subgroups within the target population sample).  We will use the findings from the PBR group, pertinent literature, and our knowledge of local contexts, and recruitment experience (Downs et al. 2010b, 2010c, 2009) to design, implement and monitor recruitment strategies and methods that pay close attention to cultural and socio-demographic diversity as well as logistical and ecological contexts (e.g. rural vs. urban settings).  
  C. Study Data Collection
 Self-administered forms and the collection of external records/extant data will be used to characterize the environments inhabited by enrolled women and children.  Since for the NCS,  environment is broadly defined to include biological, physical, chemical, and social/cultural influences on children s health and development  the major Clark contribution for this 12-month project period will be the design, testing, implementation and monitoring of methods for achieving comprehensive spatial characterization of these factors and contexts.  In order for these factors to be measured, self-administered forms will be used to delineate the spaces/micro-environments the target population inhabits during a typical year, at different times of the year.  Extant data will then be used to begin to quantify the different kinds of stressors and risk factors the population is exposed to in these micro-environments during these times.  In other words, this activity involves the mapping of time/activity/micro-environment patterns for the enrolled women and their children: Where do they spend their time, at different times of the year? What activities are they involved in? What kinds of stressors and risk factors are they exposed to   biological, chemical, physical, social, economic   and at what level?  
 To accomplish this we will use state-of-the-art synthesis of established methods that include: quantitative risk assessment (QRA); vulnerability assessment (see Downs et al. 2010 Risk Analysis paper); total human exposure (THE) assessment; systematic social observation (SSO); and various mapping and analysis techniques in Health Geographic Information Science (HealthGIS).  These methods come from diverse disciplines within the health and environmental sciences, and their synthesis and co-mingling are in line with NCS goals, and with multi-disciplinary theoretical and operational frameworks exemplified by the One Health paradigm (www.onehealthinitiative.com/), and the extensive literature on Social and Environmental Determinants of Health, and Health Disparities. column76:
The purpose of this subcontract is to provide support as necessary for the Evidence Review Team.  There will be a review of materials developed to support evidence review for the Advisory Committee on Heritable Disorders in Newborns and Children (AC).  The evidence review team will be led by Duke University.  Working under general direction of the Duke team, the MGH team will provide ongoing advice and support to the Duke group.  Specifically, MGH will finalize work on the report to MCHB and the AC regarding screening in the newborn period for hyperbilirubinemia.  
 
 The evidence review group conducts quality objective evidence reviews for up to five conditions per year, once nominated and recommended for evidence review.  Each review focuses on a nominated condition and consist of a systematic scientific literature search, appropriate analyses, summary evidence tables including key data and important findings, and identification of gaps in evidence and priorities for future research.

column76: The team at Subcontractor #1, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, shall provide a large pool of potential volunteers who are receiving homogenous irradiation to their teeth as a part of their medical treatment. This population, who have received homogeneous (and known) doses at a level appropriate to model exposures from nuclear events, are uniquely qualified to provide accurate models of the situation for which the technology is aimed: determination after-the-fact of exposure to radiation of levels that could lead to the acute radiation syndrome. The capabilities of the instruments developed at Prime Contractor and engineering subcontractors will be evaluated using volunteers at or referred by Subcontractor #1 who have received radiation doses in the pertinent dose range. The focus will be on maintaining a very low false negative rate and improving (decreasing) the false positive rate for screening at the level of 2 Gy. Using these groups of human subjects, appropriate calibration curves can be established using in vivo EPR directly in the populations of interest using the devices specifically designed for such use. Additionally, methods appropriate for use in the field can be developed and the systems can be validated with subjects who have known doses of radiation to their teeth.

Task 1: Task Management
 1.1   Kickoff Meeting
 Within seven (7) calendar days of the award of this SOW, Contractor will conduct an orientation meeting and briefing for MITRE, including the MITRE Technical Manager overseeing this tasking. The completion of this briefing will result in, but is not limited to, the following:
   Introductions of key staff
   Brief overview of the SOW administration and reporting
   Review Involution Studio s understanding of the work to be accomplished under this SOW in order to ensure that all parties have a common understanding of the work to be performed and of the respective responsibilities and obligations of the parties to that end
   Review, along with the MITRE project leader, the agreed-upon method to resolve, track, and report on issues.
 The kick off meeting will occur in person and/or via conference call. MITRE will be responsible to provide logistics for a conference call. Contractor will be responsible for developing and sharing meeting summary notes, to be delivered electronically to the MITRE Technical Manager within seven (7) calendar days of the kickoff meeting.
 1.2   Project Reporting
 To share status, accomplishments, and issues, MITRE will provide support for the following ongoing and recurring project performance artifacts.
 
 1.2.1 Monthly Progress Reporting
 Contractor will develop and deliver a Monthly Progress Report (MPR) to the MITRE Technical Manager no later than five (5) calendar days after the calendar (previously calender) month end during execution of any MITRE tasking. The report shall document in a concise form the following elements:
   Status, hourly expenditures, and a brief description of all ongoing assigned tasks and efforts and what was accomplished for each assigned task during the reporting period in comparison to planned milestones; details about problems encountered and how they are being dealt with; explanations for any tasks that are behind schedule; anticipated challenges/problems including mitigation strategies; and problems or delays experienced and actions that are proposed to alleviate the problem(s);
   Current and proposed expenditures relative to original schedule and budget, including schedule or cost variances for each task compared to the original schedule and budget;
   Activities planned for next reporting period, including anticipated staffing requirements, level of effort, and cost.
 
 Deliverables to MITRE: 
 
   Kickoff Meeting Summary Notes (within 7 days after Kickoff Meeting)
   Monthly Progress Reports (within 5 days after the month; monthly thereafter)
 
 Task 2: User Research
 MITRE requires Contractor s leverage any existing user research completed by MITRE s product team as well as conduct user interviews, with participants identified by MITRE, to fully understand users  needs and goals. This is needed for Contractor to have a complete understanding of the users, the environment in which they work, and the context of use. Expected outcomes from Contractor s interview sessions shall include immersing the design team into the context of use for the software to better understand the current pain points, unmet needs, larger workflows, and general context of use.
 
 Deliverables to MITRE: 
   Bi-weekly (every 14 days) delivery of Contractor user research assessment notes
 
 Task 3: Concept Sketches and Mockups
 Critical to the success of this activity will be Contractor s ongoing and iterative creation of concept sketches that, at a high level, articulate the recommended design patterns for the CDS repository materializing during this project. 
 
 The software development activities that MITRE is supporting rely heavily on an agile project management approach. Agile project management follows an approach in which numerous stages of the software lifecycle are addressed in short two week  sprints  of activity. MITRE requires that Contractor participate in conjunction with MITRE s bi-weekly agile process.

 Background:  Harvard School of Public Health, will assist HRET in implementation of the AHRQ SUSP Ambulatory Surgery national project through providing expert input into overall strategy, assisting in monitoring key project metrics, providing necessary checklists, assisting in the development of the course design guide and improvement materials, and in training master trainers and change agents to support the project s implementation. HSOPH will also provide feedback to Westat regarding the SOPS for Ambulatory Surgery survey that will be developed.
